\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Your full name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Thomas Patrick Brennan.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 24, Stanmore Road, Liverpool 15.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And your marital status?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I am a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  man - yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Your year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 1924.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Your year of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 1896.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Liverpool - Old Swan, Liverpool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Let's see - from - what year - 1896 I was born - and we left there about 1913.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So you lived most of your childhood in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where did you live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Stoneycroft - quite close by.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Up to the time I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 .

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So it was just those two houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Why did your family move to Stoneycroft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My father died - it was a small
er house that we were living in so we decided to go to a house which was - had more facilities than the one we were in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I had one brother and one sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was the brother older or younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 The brother was two years older and the sister was two years younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So you were the middleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well he was - fifty-two when he died and I was - let me see - about 96 for - he
 died in 1913 - thirteen - fourteen - fifteen - I was seventeen - I was seventeen when he died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You were seventeen when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How old was your father when you were born then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Thirty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He came - his people were farmers at a little town in Ireland called Drumsna in the county Leitrim.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When did he come over to England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He came over when he was about fifteen years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When he was a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He was helping his father on the farm in Ireland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What was his occupation when he was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well he came to Liverpool through a friend who had told him how wonderful it was in Liverpool but unfortunately when he ca
me here he found out the story he'd heard wasn't quite true. So he then took a position with the Liverpool - transport - Liverpool - transport company I think it was which was the old - which afterwards became the Liverpool Company and Tramways. He took a
 
position as horse keeper - being on the farm and being used to animals he took the position as the horse keeper and he also drove four-in-hands at - Aintree and any of the big meetings. And - through it he came in contact with Lord Derby and - lots of - L
ord Sefton - many of the notabilities in the local area. Yes, yes, that's right. Very - you see, very great horseman - he could do anything with horses so that's why. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he have any other job after that at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, well from that - when the
 horse cars were finished he came then onto the horse trams and he was - a - a driver with the tramway company driving the old - buses between what was then Old Swans and the Pierhead. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He did that up to the time he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Died. That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he do any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, he was - its - in those days the nine hour a day job were the split - split working. So very often he would start at five in the morning and he would be working 'til five or six at night with a break in between for - meals. Very hard, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, he was never out of work - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, I would say she was about - five years - five or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So she was about thirty?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I would say that - yes. But with Irish people - they never kept their birth certificates so you had to judge. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was she an Irish girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 She was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was she born in Ireland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 She was. He - crossed over to Ireland and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  in Ireland and brought her back to Liverpool. That's right - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Had she any jobs before she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. She was - also a farmer's daughter. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So she helped on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes, yes. About I 
would say - oh - six or seven miles from my father's home. But on the opposite side of the Shannon. She was in Roscommon which come under the same - Drumsna - but the Shannon divided the two parts up. She was on the Roscommon side, my father was on the Le
itrim side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she work after she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. Not at all - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she do any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not at all - no. The housekeeping was - oh just to look after the home all the time up to the time she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How many rooms were there in the house at Old Swan?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, it was a small house. It was a four roomed house with no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 
accommodation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  for baths. A toilet outside - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Two bedrooms upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Two bedrooms upstairs - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And a parlour and a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right - that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have a back kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, just the two rooms downstairs - yes. And a very comfortable house although it was - as I say - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It's what you do to a house isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did anyone else besides yourself and your parents and brother and sister live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not at all - no. We was there all the time. We had quite a number of Irish people used to visit us and amongst them w
as a relation of my - my wife's - I'm sorry - my mother's sister's boy - had one boy and he was a doctor. He came over from Dublin university and he used to come - used to do locums here. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And he would stay with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No he used - no h
e didn't stay with - he would come and visit us and - sometimes come for two or three hours and - and if we were ill he'd -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not at all - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was - done at home. Yes, and even the baking as well - yes, oh yes, real mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother or father make or mend the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I think everything we had was - well, she would repair - sew buttons on and do generally - but wou
ldn't make any clothes. No, no. You see, with Irish people they don't get the chance - of opportunities to learn as you do in this country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were the clothes you had new or secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - we - one thing about my father although he was very ha
rdworking and wasn't too well off each year we had a new suit of clothes. Yes, we - had a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 On a special occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. What happened was we were interested in church work - we all children. My father and my mother were both very good Catholi
cs and as such we were in the choir, on the altar, my sister was interested in church work as well. So, and with being in the choir each year my father used to take us up to a local }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 tailor}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  and as a little boy I always - I can remember it today - standing o
n the counter whilst he measured me. Now in those days there were - what's to say - knee trousers with the long stockings - turned down stockings - and shoes. And I will say this, we were always nicely dressed. Very nicely dressed - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about shoes - were shoes ever new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, always shoes - no, we never bought anything secondhand. Always bought everything new.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your father mend the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. They were all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Sent to the cobblers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - you see - no - he - with him being a farmer, I suppose, and working for them, they become rather in the way that the wife must do the house side of it and I will do the - keep the h
ome going and look after it so he didn't - I now wash up and take my - help my wife in everything - but that wasn't - in those days - it wasn't done you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He didn't ever do anything like the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Any decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Any improvement to the home in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well he could do a bit of joinery. I know we had a - a kind of fencing outside he did and he also built a shed at the back. But anything very - that he wanted doing well he would bring a man in to do it. Oh yes. He was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he ever dress you or undress you as a child or bath you or read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. He was a typical - he was a typical - you see, with Irish people they're brought up hard - by that I mean, lovingly b
ut hard and consequently the husband does the husband's work and the mother does the mother's work. So the mother would - the mother would do all those kind of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I think we all pretty well 
together - it might - to church you see you'd go to church at different times. Mind you in those days people didn't go out quite as much as they do today. When we were young we used to take the family over the water and take to Southport and Blackpool and
 different places but in those days they didn't. You just stayed in your own little area. That's right - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he ever look after you when your mother was out - if she had to go out at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I don't remember my mother ever being away from the h
ome. No, she was never ill - she was very - being Irish you see they were strong and I don't remember - except towards latterly my father was ill but up to that time -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When he got older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have any tasks that you had to carry out regularly at home to help your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Not particularly. I - I would help in the house - bring the coal in and - perhaps go - my father of course would - if there were any wood to be chopped he would chop it and that kind of
 thing but on a Saturday - you see, during the week I was pretty well employed with going to - I was an altar server - used to serve - and of course there were services twice a week in the evenings and I was a choir boy so there was always a couple of nig
hts choir practice. There was no wireless and television in those days. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But you were pretty busy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes. And Saturday of course it was free. Now, just close to us was a green-grocer and I used to go and help him on a Saturday - yes, that's right, I worked for him. For the - the wonderful sum of one shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you get started on that did someone suggest it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I thought - I think - I thought of it myself. 'Course boys as a rule looked round for something to do - more so now
adays than they did in those days but my father thought I'd be better if I was - doing something and out of - any mischief so consequently I worked from - about - I think it was about eight in the morning 'til about eight at night - for one shilling, yes.
 
And you used to get fruits - you'd get probably fruit - something like that. But - it wasn't done - it wasn't really needed. It was just a case of well do it because it keeps your mind occupied. Yes, well a shilling was nothing really. 'Course in those da
ys, as I say, you could have a day out for a shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you continue to do these jobs in the home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Probably I would if I was in the house but unfortunately I was one of the probably general - at the time - boys generally 
at the time - I had to work nine hours a day. Now when I first started working in the Post Office I started at - an office about two - two or three miles from home and it was a nine hour day and sometimes it was a split duty so consequently the whole of t
he day I was pretty well out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You were involved in working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Getting there and coming home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right. If mother wanted anything doing, say bring coal in anything like that I'd help. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 There wasn't anything specific?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. And everything was fairly handy you see being a small house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So there wasn't much running around to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your brother and sister have regular jobs to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, my brother was perhaps a little bit unus
ual. He - got in with - a baker - 'cos in those days people - used to - not like that - it wasn't wrapped and that kind of thing you went to the bakers for - and they had delivery vans. Now, just close to home was a man named Harbridge and my brother took
 a liking to Mr Harbridge, I don't know why, but not only did he do Saturdays with him but he often went in the evenings and worked in the evenings. Oh yes. Unfortunately - unfortunately he got into bad habits there because he started smoking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did the older children - your brother was older than you and you were older than your sister -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he or you help your sister with things she found difficult such as dressing or undressing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No. Being a girl and of course parents in t
hose days - very old fashioned - so mother looked after my - sister and being the only child - girl - I think she was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 She felt the boys shouldn't handle her in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right. She was - what shall I say - petted a lot by both father and
 mother so she was a little - on her own - so we didn't - we never dressed her - no no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she help you at all in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, they just - it was really no need - she just had her own friends and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh yes. I would say round about - well, nine to ten at the very latest - sometimes earlier. But we were never up late - no. In those days of course there were no television or wireless or that - you just - when it beca
me dark you went in - and - probably there wasn't a lot to do - might read something and then of course go to bed early - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When we were very young she may have helped us - to undress and that but as we grew up we - pretty well looked after ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What age would you say you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I would say about - round about ten - probably ten or eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you share the bedroom with anyone?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 With another brother - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have a bed each or a double bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 We had a double bed - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where would your sister sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My sister - of course being a smaller house - slept in the front with my father and mother - and there was - I thi
nk it was a screen between the beds. Yes, with being a smaller house of course that's the way they had to do it. That's right - quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - in the - I think we bathed in the - what would be the living room. We had on
e of these big - zincish baths and be bathed there and - probably about - mother bathed us - mother did everything as they do - would bath us and of course when we were old enough to do it we could do it ourselves. Boys - as you get older you get a bit sh
y and you do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I would say once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was a regular thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 The same. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Coincided with your bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. I will say mother was - and father - particular about that. We always had nice clothes and were always changed - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 In the - what we would call the lounge - the front room, that's right - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you always eat in there or were there any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No we might - whatever was handy for mother. If mother - if mother wanted it in the - the second room but not - I think mostly it was in the front room. Yes, that's right - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where did your mother cook - in the back room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
That's right - yes. It had a stove - well now, wait a minute - now if I remember rightly and I think I'm right here - the - you cooked on the fire - yes, it was all - I don't remember - I think we had an -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have any ovens there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
I think we had one. You know very old fashioned of course. And - that's right - and then if we were out - a bit late coming in - put the meal in the oven and with it being the fire it kept warm - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she ever have a gas fire when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No. No. We had gas for lighting. I think first of all we oil lamps if I remember rightly, yes, oh yes. I don't - I'm not sure when the gas came but that came in later on. Ye
s, I remember how, I can remember her having oil lamps. You know, the big oil lamps. That's right. Well of course you see in Ireland the same thing happened so it wouldn't be anything strange to them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 They'd be used to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, she was, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well it would be eight o'clock because we'd have to go to school for nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What member of the family would be present - what about your father - he would have left earlier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My father - yes, that's right - my father would have it before he went down -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would have got that - would he have got it himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, my mother was always there - the old fashioned mother - always there to look after us - that's right - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did you usually have to eat and drink for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well if I remember rightly we had tea plenty of bread and butter and bacon and - an egg occasionally - bacon and egg. Oh yes, we were very well - as regards food and clothing we were well looked after - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you mostly have a cooked breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have anything different on Sunday for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I think mother would get a small joint on a Sunday. No, no, for breakfast would be the same - oh yes, yes, yes. You s
ee, nowadays we - I have this shredded wheat and all this kind of food well there wasn't - in the old days there wasn't. It was just - just what we call the plain foods. Bacon - and of course bacon and butter and these kind of things were very much cheape
r because of course wages were very much less. A person say getting eighteen shillings a week could keep a family on it. Want an hour - that's an hours overtime now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You say you had a joint on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What else would you have with the joint?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Always vegetables and - and potatoes - always plenty potatoes. Now, us being they liked their potatoes in their jackets so they would be cooked and on a separate plate and you'd have them - now, with being Irish of course we used to very ofte
n get sacks of potatoes from Ireland and I can always remember how lovely they were because with the - the Irish way of cooking them in their jackets as they called 'em - cooking with the skins on - as you took the skin off they would be - oh, sometimes a
 quarter of an inch of - of lovely - not brown - no - like all floury - yes - oh yes, really lovely. I don't think the - the potatoes now are anything like they were, No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What would you have had for a pudding on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Mostly rice puddings I think - rice puddings and milk puddings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about during the week - what kind of mid-day meal would you have had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I think much the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you give me some examples of things you remember you had for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. Well, 
I think it was - meat was very cheap then so we'd have - steak and different things like that, on a Friday always fish and - always vegetables and that. But - I think probably there were more varieties in those days and - and as I say meat was cheaper. An
d - another thing there was no fridges in those days so - a - a - butcher if he had meat he'd almost present it to you. That's right - rather than put it in the fridge. There were no fridges. Yes, oh yes, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would puddings during the week be mostly milk puddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Mostly milk puddings, yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No sort of pies or suet puddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well my mother used to make pies - I don't remember so much suet puddings, I was a little - I've forgotten -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What would you have had for evening meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well very often my wife used to - I'm sorry - my mother used to get - bones and different things, you know, what do they - bacon boil - Irish people - what do they call them now - they have - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 The breast bone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right
 - yes. She'd always have soups in the evening. And very often we'd have friends from Ireland that - with my father being Irish of course they had a little Irish circle and very often they would come in and have supper with us and might be sometimes of co
urse with dad having - if it - if it was on certain duites we'd have our meal in the evening and it was always plenty of soup - plenty of food. There was never any shortage of food in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My mother did - for a time - that's right. We used to take it in tins down to - bake shop. Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she make her own jam or bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, there wasn't - I - I don't think as I remember was the facility you know its not like you have now you can do it here or there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she ever make pickles or wine or any medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was there any beer brewed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, if there was any beer wanted - dad used to bring it in. He liked a glass of beer but that was another story. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did they buy any tinned vegetables or fruit or dried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I don't think - they would get some tinned but there wasn't the t
inned foods in those days. It was pretty well all fresh food. Occasional might get a tin of something but - such as soups and all those kind of things were made from natural things - yes, oh yes, it was later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did they keep any livestock for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, the only thing they kept was - I took fancy to doves and my father - I don't know where he got them from but I had - three or four lovely doves - my - and he made a cage for them and - I really loved them but unfortunately round our neighbourh
ood there were a lot of cats and one day I came down and all the doves had gone so - so I didn't have any more doves. Oh yes. I was upset - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you take care of the doves while you had them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right - oh yes, yes. And of course dad would take - keep an eye on them too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you say you had meat mostly every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes, mostly - oh yes, yes. I will say for food and for clothing we were always well looked after - oh yes. They very hard - my parents - my father was hardworking but he was very good in that respect - we never went short of anything. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you ever get some extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, that never happened - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, of course with a - a wife she always gives her husband a little extra taster. But I think the - the rules very fair. I mean if there was anything in the house it was shared. I don't think my father - had this way. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, there was no - talk you know as children do - there was no - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No we had what was cooked because in the main we - we weren't faddy. Children I don't think were as faddy in those days as they are today so what was cooked - we were healthy children and what we had we enjoyed and there was no - no special foods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh well, of course, they wouldn't like that but I - I - I don't remember ever leaving anything - I think that we always - whatever we had 
was always eaten - oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh no, you - well, it was always handy and you always had - if - if it was nearer to anyone it would be handed to you. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh if - yes, if you wanted - there was never any shortage of food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - we were always expected - oh yes, well - we were trained really to - to sit at the table properly. Oh yes, father was very particular on those points - oh yes, and mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Could you bring a toy or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not - I don't remember doing it - no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When could you leave the table - what was the procedure?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh, at the end of the meal you left the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have to wait until everyone finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 As a rule - but if you wanted - if you asked to leave the table you could but as a rule we all left together - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, all together, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Pretty well, yes. Oh yes, I think you do that naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
How was the meal served - how did your mother serve the meal - would she serve it straight from the saucepans onto plates and then put the plates on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would she use a serving dish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh no, I think with th
e house being small I think she kind of had to have the plates and put the - put the different foods on it - oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What order were you served in? Who was served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, father always first if he was at the table and of course th
e oldest would bet the next and so on and son on. Yes. Sometimes because they - with being the only girl she would probably get it but as a rule it usually was - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where did your sister sit before she could feed herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I've got a feeling we
 had a high chair - I'm not quite sure but I - I remember that as regards that - vaguely in my mind and I always remember that when we learned to walk of course nowadays children walk and seem to - grow up very, very quickly - they're not babies very long
 - but we had one of those gadgets for - four sides and a round top and - and - and little wheels on it and we were put in that - you couldn't fall because the round ring on - would hold you up and you kind of made your way about on - until you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who fed the little one while she was in the high chair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My mother would do that - yes. My mother would do that - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How old would you have been when you were eating with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I would say about three - two or three. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, well - quiet - she was very quiet and - oh yes, very homely and very kind. Oh my mother was very kind indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she show you a lot of affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, yes, she was a lovely mother - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was she demonstrative or didn't she show it very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, quiet - Irish type you know, quiet and easy going and - I think you see with country people land brought up - the women folk are kind of the people that look after the menfolk and they g
row up that way and consequently they take that it's their duty to - no, no. That's right - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 If you had any worries could you have shared them with her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I would say yes - but - I suppose with being - you see, mostly with being connected wit
h church they might discuss you with one of the priests if you were friendly with
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Rather than with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I suppose you would if it was something very intimate you might speak to the mother but I don't k
now - you didn't - I don't remember us having any - very, very - yes, oh yes, oh yes, oh yes, oh yes. Well I think I would do so more with my mother than I would with my father because my father was inclined - being a man as I said, you know, been brought
 up - he wouldn't perhaps understand like a mother. Mother is the person that - oh yes, the mother - that's right, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you talk quite a lot to the priests when you were a young lad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, well - see, from when I was - I started ser
ving at church when I was about six or seven - I was very young - and I happened to drop in with a boy who was very, very - well we called him Holy Charlie - he was a very holy chap and he was a - a wonderful character although - people would say he's odd
 
nowadays but - he was really one - and he taught me to serve and consequently - I - I don't know whether it was but priests in those days were more fatherly and - than they are today. If they come into a - oh yes, they come into the house and know every m
e
mber of the family. Now even the director - the old Cannon - of course he was Father in those - Father in cloths in those days - he new me as Tommy and Billy and that and he took an interest in all the boys - he'd take you out and explain the stars to you
 and - and - all to train you in every way - so I think the training I got as a - as a altar boy stood me in stead in after life. Oh yes, I look on the clergy that I met as - as real fatherly figures. Very kindly, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You said your father wasn't so easy to talk to but were you able to talk to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, yes. He was more shall I say set - I won't say old fashioned - put it that way. And - oh yes, he was very, very kindly in every -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, oh yes, he was always affectionate - oh yes, I must say - and when he died was terribly upset. Took me a long time to get over it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He was a young man wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He was. That's right - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - we had respect for our parents in those days. I - I know my father was strict in so much that - if we were very naughty he would get a strap out. I don't - I don't remember - I remember him threatening a couple of time - I may have felt it onc
e - once - but I - it never - it wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 A frequent thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh no, no, no,. No, no. I think he was so strict in his way if he said a thing it was done. There was no - there was no - no - and you couldn't say to him so-and-so, so-and-so - if he s
aid a thing it had to be done. That's right. Yes. I think - well, I think in the old days the parents were like that - more - stricter in every way. But - and of course the homes were better for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother and sister in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, I think - I don't - I think it more or less came naturally to us by the way we were brought up you know. We were always respected one another and got on well with one another. But of course we had our own playmates. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You went your own ways sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - yes, that's right. Mater of fact, with the brother being two years older he was always felt he was a little bit - more the -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, I don't remember them saying it. I suppose you naturally would - if somebody hits you you kind of - but - wouldn't encourage you to strike other children. No, no, oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I think that with seeing that we went to church on Sunday and did what we could regards the church work and that - they - they looked on us we would - set out and become good citizens, put it that way. But I will t
ell you one little point - when I was - as I told you that they wanted me to go into the priesthood and my father being more or less - not a - he was strict but - he had a lot to do with clergy and in Ireland the clergy were thought so much of that you ha
d
 almost to be something out of the ordinary to become a priest. And that was kind of drilled in you - in other words the respect you gave them was a - a very great respect and consequently when you - as you were growing up you thought you wouldn't make th
e grade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You thought you weren't good enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - that's right. Now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did the priests say to you about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well the priest - on several occasions I had the chance - I met a priest from South Africa and I would probabl
y if I'd have had - shown willing he would have taken me back with him, but - all the time - the back of my mind I thought I wouldn't make the grade, you feel that way you see. In other words comes back to you underestimate your abilities and - whilst I w
as - at - serving at church one of the men that was a member of the congregation - his name was Lin - was - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was he polish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no - oh - I'll think of his name in a minute. Anyway there were two brothers and they were starting in the film in
dustry and Father Russell said to me - oh Tommy, I have a job for you. Seeing that you won't go away for the church this gentleman would like you to - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 go to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  the firm and as - as an office boy and start up with the firm. Now they were film renters. In those
 days films were flickers - if you wanted to see a film you went to a park - mostly the - they came with the traveling shows and you stood in a marquee and then they flicked onto a screen and - you know - because - that's where the word flickers came beca
u
se - electricity wasn't up to the standard it is today. Well when my - my father, of course, being old fashioned said - you're not going into that because there's no future. You're going into the Post Office. So, of course we had to - if he said a thing w
e
ll that was the law you see. And so consequently I went into the Post Office and my brother went into the Post Office and finally my sister so - we all - we all - Post Office people. Whiteskill was the man's name - Mr Whiteskill. He was a film renter and 
a
fterwards he became one of the biggest film renters in North of England. Rather strange he lived in Wootton Road, quite close Bishop Street. He died three or four years ago and I - I often chatted with him. I said to him one day - I nearly became a member
 of your firm. He said - well, I think you did the best thing. But I don't know - it - we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You can't look back on life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You can't - you can't - you can't - no. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, we were always - they were always particular about us being clean and our shoes polished and - a credit to them, that's the way, yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 We never heard any - bad language of any kind - no. No. No.
 Then you might hear, you see - where we lived - being - as I said - four roomed houses you - you didn't get quite as nice a class of people as you do later on - and therefore you would hear it probably outside but we would never bring it in the house - o
h no. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And your parents didn't swear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not - no, not to join in. If you were asked - yes but you weren't expected to - no. No, no. Unless you were asked - yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well he would just say you mustn't do it and you knew that if he said you mustn't do it that was it you - you wouldn't go against him because although he - he didn't - 
he never had occasion, I don't think, to chastise us but we knew that what he said was law - we never questioned it at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember any occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, we might have come in late - when we were told to come in
 at a certain time and then might have said something that they disapproved of but - I don't remember - no, I'd remember - I just don't - I can only remember one occasion that he - said go up to bed and - came up with the strap, and I don't think he strap
ped me. When it got to that stage - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember how you felt about being told off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, I think we were brought up - with, as I say, going to church and that - we were brought up more or less to obey if we were told to do a thing. And 
- we didn't think anything about it, no, we did - in those days - 'course there weren't the attractions there are today and no - we just lived like the normal life - playing and making our own fun, you know, in those days you made - you made what you call
e
d a peggy and a stick and - you had games - such as ton weight heavy on and - all the boys games and we - enjoyed little things more so that today. We - we never had any expensive toys or anything - at Christmastime - I remember one Christmas my mother bo
u
ght me a kettle drum, I think she paid a shilling for it and of course that was quite - quite a lot then and I treasured this kettle drum - I think another day - another time they bought me a little wheelbarrow for - little child's wheelbarrow and - yes, 
o
h yes. Now, as regards riding a bicycle - you see children nowadays with bicycles don't you - well in - in our day there weren't the cycles that - and I'd chummed in with a boy at school, his name was - Graham - Willie Graham, and his father was a joiner,
 
a very - they were a very, very nice family. He was the head joiner at a - a Borax Works in Dubb Lane - disappeared now - they made borax. Well he would make kites - he made kites. He made all kinds of toys and we would go up to the Grahams and they would
 
have - take them out to some fields - quite a lot of fields nearby and they'd fly the kites - and - he was a wonderful man - wonderfully kindly man - I always - and rather strange when he - when he'd - when he was dying he asked his - one of his daughters
 
to go and tell me would I come and see him. Oh yes, yes. We were very fortunate - we had some very, very - people that - wouldn't say were well off because there were no motor cars - oh no, but - but we were very happy in the friends we had - oh yes, yes.
 Yes. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you say you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both you parents or did one play a greater part than the other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I wouldn't say so. My mother was a mother with - as I said, with the training she had in Ireland 
- and - with - with a woman in - in - in - on farming and those places her duty was in the home and her - her husband's duty was on - and - and - we were brought up more or less in that style. My father would - if for instance my mother told us to do some
thing and we didn't do it quickly and my father was there he'd say do it and it was done you see, there was no - no quibbling about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, mother would get a cake and - give it -
 perhaps bring two or three little friends in. But it wasn't - not like you have today you know, but just a little party and one or two children that you played with round about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It would be a different day though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, make you - she would to her best extent - oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have any presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well of course there wasn't a lot of - money in those days and - I don't think we expected them quite the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you get anything at all on your birthday - can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Probably an odd little present from one of - from mother or father but our - probably - chum together - put together and got it but - I don't think - I don't remember getting anything special - because I think children in those days didn't want thi
ngs like they do today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 They didn't expect it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember anything you did with your mother and father on a Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, yes - we all went to church together. That's if father wasn't working - as a rule fathe
r - I think mostly I remember him being off - and we always had a - a turkey - or a goose from Ireland. As a matter of fact I think sometimes we'd have three - it was nothing to have three - geese - I - oh yes, they were all - we were never short of anyth
i
ng Christmas you see and - we would get potatoes from Ireland and different things so we always - and mother always made - oh yes, we were always happy - oh yes, we always remembered the Christmas time. Then on top of that with going to church sometimes t
o get little things from the clergy. They might give you a little present of some kind or other. So really looking back - I look back on Easter and Christmas as hap - very happy days. Not much - not much -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not much material things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no, but - 
it was - it was the hap - happy atmosphere. 'Cos I always remember when I was in the - France sometimes on the back of the Somme and Passion Day - oh, they were terrible times. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 
I can always remember, looking back, oh yes, and being an altar boy - I can pic
ture the sun shining through the window - windows and the - the incense and the coloured vestments and everything with - kind of everything was done so - it was done right to the book. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
And - it slipped - I remember music - we had a lovely choir of about th
irty or forty - and singing - oh it was - you know - you've many a time when you've been wet through to the skin you'd be nothing to eat and you'd be perhaps in the middle of a terrible bombardment and that - you didn't know when - whether you were going 
t
o be here for the next hour or so and - then I used to look back on those days. It was - yes - they were not - there weren't days when you spent a lot of money but you had that happiness of the - of your boyhood and - and growing up and - the simple thing
s in life - oh they did - great pleasure - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What would you do in the afternoon on Christmas Day - would you go out or stay in the house? Or would you have any relatives in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I don't think - we had - see, close by we had Catholic fri
ends and we might go in to see them but I think in the main we spent it in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You spent it together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes. As a matter of fact when you had your Christmas dinner and that you'd be tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Unfortunately no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was there anyone who sang in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well we were both - we all in the choir - but we didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But not at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. But at - we'd have choir practice twice a week and - for about 
two hours and we had a - a wonderful choir master. He afterwards went to the B.B.C. Oh yes. And the organist was a man named Willinsky - he was wonderful player. And we had - we'll say - what - about twenty - twenty or thirty boys and - about ten or twent
y men. We had a lovely choir. And I remember at Christmas time we sang the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 Hallelujah}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 Chorus and - but when I hear it now I don't think they sung it any better than what we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It has a magic when you look back hasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, oh yes, oh yes.
 My days were - the church - with being connected with the church and that - most of my life was - as youngsters - was built up with it - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Right from your early memories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Always. Always got to church - oh yes, oh yes. And I think to - if 
anyone spoke to me I would say that - yes, that's right - I - I would say that - I wouldn't wish it any other way. If I had to go back or - well, it is. And even now you see I do - well, four or five - four hours a day at - helping in different ways and -
 
well, I suppose. Well I suppose as you get older you - you think and you see all your friends, dif - well, I was at a funeral today. You see different ones - some die - this chap died but I was only speaking to him a week or so ago and it comes - it kind 
of gives you that little shock, well we're only here for a short time. And you think to yourself well, I must make the grade. I must save my soul if I can. Probably its - its - its - way you've been brought up to or - but I think myself -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It's just what you feel really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And it gives you pleasure to sort of do your bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes. Well, as a matter of fact, I get just as much enjoyment in life after helping a person - I don't want anything for it - if I know I've helped a person or - done them a good - well, I get a kick out of it - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And this is a reward in itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh, it is, it is, it is. And they get ple - and you know very well you've pleased someone and - and - they have a good thought for you - etcetera. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were there any books in the home when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Just - magazines - there were - the - I was allowed to buy - buy boys books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You got the boys adventure books?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. Things of that sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about newspapers and things for your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
I think we had the - Evening paper - the Echo. I don't remember the daily paper so much because with father being at work and - we were at school we didn't have much time - no, but I think we got an evening paper - the Echo - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember your parents reading any books at all that you had in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, rather }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 strangely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  - with them being the farmer type they weren't reading - they weren't the reading types you see. They might probably get - a weekend paper like f
ancy bits - something like that to read but in the main - we seemed to have company in the evenings - we had to - there weren't a lot -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 There wasn't much time for reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. And then in those days there wasn't the facilities they have toda
y. We had a library - the Carnegie Library - at Lister drive where we would get books from if we wanted them but - normally - we didn't - no, we didn't - like today you go to Smiths and buy - either paper backs or you can buy different books - but in our 
day there weren't - didn't seem to be the books that we have today - books are more in plentiful supply today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you have gone to the library yourself as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, I used to go to the library and very often I took books down for the teac
her to change them. Ask me and during lunch time - yes, and then I'd get a book if I wanted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was this a novel for you or was it to do with your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - I think they were mostly novels or - yes, anything that would interest him. That's right - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, the only - only - funerals of people round about I knew - not of - in the family.
 The first death we had in the family was my dear dad. He was the first one - that's right - yes, that was the first. But of course I did - with being an altar boy I did frequently come - I suppose that's - oh, I came into contact with - yes, I used to go
 out to different cemeteries with the priest for funerals. Oh yes. So I came a lot in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Any interesting tales to tell about these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, coming back from the funerals we - a Cannon very often - accompanied us on the way and he would chat abo
ut school life and things of interest and some - he was most interesting really - real - real English Catholic gentleman and he was interesting what he spoke about. But I can't say I remember anything particular about that. I remember - an incident when I
 
was serving during the opening of the Carmelite Convent in Knotty Ash when Whiteside - before Liverpool became an Archbishop - Bishop Whiteside was there and what a wonderful man he was, you know, very straight and he had very, very - holy and very human.
 
I was a little altar boy carrying the - mitre I think it was. Well that's - one of - one of the little things that stick in my mind. Special occasions like Easter and Christmas when we had - something special in the choir to sing which we had very often. 
In those days of course there wasn't plain chants - we had the - different Masses by the different - oh, wonderful musician and - consequently it was - oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about mourning clothes for the funeral you attended - what kind of mourning clothes would the people have worn?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - in the people - people always wore black in those days. Yes, it - it was one of the things that people did - they - they - when there was a funeral they all went out and bought black. Now it was - recognised
 thing. You wouldn't see anyone in - in a light suit or anything. No it was - at the time - yes, that's right. Not - to everyone even to the - people that - you know - were very poor. They would try as hard as possible to get black. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - yes, we went - we visited different - Irish friends that my father had and he, in his turn, if he could - chaps coming over from Ireland and some cases hadn't 
a job to go to and he was - with knowing quite among the gentlemen in the town would be able to get them placed. And of course at that time work was hard to get - there was a lot of unemployment and so we - people would come to the house and visit us - fr
o
m Irish people as you know and we would also - I remember as a boy of - what - about eight or nine - going to a wedding in those days. But they weren't - nowadays - people have a wedding, they have say a - a hall or somewhere in - in our day it was at hom
e - all the friends were invited in. Oh yes, it was more a homely affair, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would have taken you visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Father and mother - we - we - oh yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you ever taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 With mother - yes. Of course - in our da
y - like early on in the early years parents - fathers didn't do the shopping like they do today. Well the father was the working person of the house and the mother was the one that managed the house. We would go - we would go shopping with mother to carr
y the - the bag or whatever it was. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you ever go out just with your father for anything or anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Except to church. He would go - come to church with us - that's right - yes. No, I don't remember going anywhere - 'course nowadays paren
ts go out together and go over say to West Kirkby or Hawick, Southport, Blackpool, places like that but in our day people didn't travel quite as much - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 They stayed put?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - and yet traveling was much cheaper than it is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember any other outings with your parents - at Bank Holiday for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, I think that - Bank Holidays with us children we'd probably go to the parks and - with a little crowd - entertain ourselves. But I don't think parents there agai
n bothered much with - Bank Holiday - no. If - I suppose very often my father probably would be working then you see because - in olden days the Bank Holiday and the Sunday was treated just as a working day. Nowadays of course they get extra pay for it bu
t - but - no, no, it was just part of a working day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you ever go away for a holiday as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes. My father - for some reason - would never go back over to Ireland. Promised many times but he never went back. But we as children traveled over to Ireland - we'd spend four or five weeks - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How often would you have done this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, year - yearly or every other year. Oh yes. As a youngster I went over to Ireland quite a lot and my uncle used to meet me at the station with a Jumpson Car.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You enjoyed those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh very much - yes. And in - in those days its mostly being summer time, very often it was harvest time - they were getting the hay - they hay in and at - if was a busy day and then - in the evening we'd hav
e a dance - a couple of people would come with a fiddle and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 melodeons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  - a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 melodeons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  about at the time. I remember quite well because I - I became friendly with one of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 melodeon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  players - she was a very nice girl and - but for some reason - of c
ourse a lot of Irish people went to America - and she went to America and I corresponded with her, even during the war - that's right - and when - the war was over she wrote to me as she was doing very regularly and asked me to go to Ireland to meet her. 
S
he was coming over on a - on a - on a holiday. But unfortunately the - the black and tan trouble and the Irish trouble was on at the time and my uncle wrote and said whatever you do don't come over because one day we have the black and tans, another day w
e
 have the military and another day we have the - I.R.A. and we very often have to sleep out in byres and that because the military or the forces take over the - property and take over the whole place and - you just have to - you've got to be very careful 
what you say - you mustn't be friendly with one otherwise the other people come along. So I didn't go after all - consequently the romance broke up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When you were young you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 With your brother and sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not very often we 
used to go - I'd go on my own. Sometimes my brother would go on his trip over and we had another cousin over in West Port which was - that's - some distance away and my brother would - stayed at West Port - I didn't go over there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You didn't always go together then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You'd go at different times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you spend Saturdays in those days? You worked didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - yes. I - yes. Pretty well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Saturday was a long working day for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was. Yes, that's right. Yes, pretty well - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What kind of a day was Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, Sunday was always church day. I served eight o'clock, came home for breakfast, then - we had a general - high mass at eleven. Served eleven. And then we had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 children\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 service at - I think it was three thirty - I served at that and then Benediction in the evening at half past six which in our day was very well attended. There was no evening ser - evening Mass so Benediction was it and - the Cannon was 
- had - many occasions managed to get someone special to speak and consequently it was very well attended - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about playing games on Sunday - if you had any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, on Sunday - rather strange - children didn't play out as much as they do today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - it - they didn't - it was never mentioned really. It was just the fact that - it wasn't done. It didn't - Sunday was kept - as a rule people had - shall we say no, they used to call them Sunday clothes - you don't bother today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You had special clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, as a rule, yes. You'd have - you'd dress nicely of course for Sunday. And of course you wouldn't like to go out and - soil them, that
 kind of thing. So Sunday was kept - I think most people and even when you look back from today it was a very quiet day, Sunday, it was respected and - you seemed - see people more so than today going to their own church. No - of course there wasn't the b
uses and there was no motor transport and of course most of the - horses and carts was used during the week for - work so they just come out - so mostly it was very quiet - quiet day. Much different from today. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your parents attend Mass on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, my mother and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What services would they go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well as a rule they would go to the eleven o'clock service, yes, mother would be getting the breakfast and mother would probably go to an earlier - Mass. Generally there were ab
out three on Sunday - three or four on Sunday so she would probably go to nine and then - she'd leave the breakfast and then we'd have our breakfast and then go to eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your mother go again with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. No, the mother was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Your father would go at eleven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right - yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would either of them go to the evening service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Occasionally. They didn't go every week. Occasionally they went. Of course on - on - sometimes on Sunday fath - dad was wor
king you see so - of course he wouldn't be able to go. And then of course mother was generally - very often busy and that - things to do in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So that didn't include Sunday school for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well Sunday afternoon was called - was called Sunday school - that's right, and the school children attended that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 This was a particular service for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 For them, that's right. Yes it was - and it was very well attended the children. It was more or less - instructions as well. There was ins
truction of - different articles. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Not with the Sunday school but with the choir we had a - each year we used to go to - mostly Southport and one of the - the priest who had - particular interest in
 the choir would go - go with us and - we'd have everything laid on. A really - really good day - oh yes. Well, he'd take us into - the show - and I remember we had - in those days we had kind of a gadget you sat on and it spun round and you're thrown off
 and you got on it again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 And of course the roundabouts and - he would join in with everything.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 Would they pay for the roundabouts and things?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, they seemed to have some arrangement where they'd give a certain amount of - a sum you see and th
en of course all the children could - have - go wherever they liked. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did they provide tea for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. I remember in those days from Liverpool to Southport the - we - the walked down to Knotty Ash station which wasn't far away - and you 
could go to Southport for one and threepence return - day return. And with children it was half price so that was - that was about - to us - sevenpence ha'penny. And I remember I was fourteen at - fourteen or fifteen at the time when I went and Father Rus
sell who at the time took the choir said to me, well, Tommy, I'm getting you for half fare. He thought it was quite a joke.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And any other activities other than this outing - you would have choir practices?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right. Well, to encourage th
e boys to go to choir practice - the choir master bought a set of cricket - cricket outfit - the pads and bats and all the gear and quite was - there was a park quite close by and of course you never knew when you were going to practice whether you were g
o
ing to have a - a - or a game of cricket or whether you were going to practice. So very often that was an encouragement to go. Yes, yes. And then of course if there was something special on you might ask to see if the boys were interested to have - he'd s
ay well the boys sing it the best I'll give them a - a sixpence - which was quite a lot in those days We'd all have a go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So this would be once a week practice or more than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Twice a week practice - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Any other activities }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 run by}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, I don't - remember anything. Oh, we used to go to town to sing with other choirs - like little competitions. We often - St Mary's, Highbury Street in the town - one of the old churches there - they had a very nice choir and we'd go 
down and compete. Yes, and I - I - think one or two other - I forget the other churches. Yes, oh yes, have a little - it was like an evening out for us and we thought it was quite good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you belong to any other club organised by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, as I grew up I joined the Young }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 Men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What age would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - I - would be - about sixteen or seventeen. Yes. When -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What would that entail?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, they had a billiard team - they had a football team - h
ad club meetings you know, just general activities. Had competitions - very - knock-out competitions. Mostly billiards. Darts weren't on the go in those days so much as you hear of them to - today. And then of course you met other - ooh little cards but I
 
wasn't great card player but some of the boys used to - lose quite a little bit at it. Yes, that - they weren't supposed to play for - it was only a case of playing for ha'pennies you know, halfpennies but - 'course sometimes when there was no one about t
hey'd - stuck up - played bank when they shouldn't have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Not - I can't remember said out loud. We used to say grace but it wasn't said out loud - we just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You said it yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes - that's
 right - yes. Yes. And at - of course at school you said grace before you left - and when you came back to school - after meals - oh yes. So - they - if you forgot at mealtimes it was said at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, 
we - we said them individually as we went to bed but - there again at school we'd have school prayers when we left school and then we just say our won little prayers going to bed. Yes, that's right. Yes, not - general of course. 'Course mind you in Irelan
d
 they say their prayers together more than they do here - yes, but - I think that - when they come to England they - they don't just say things are quite - quite as much - no, because they follow the English tradition and - some are not always for the bes
t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father take an interest in politics? Do you know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, at the time I think - Labour of course hadn't - the pull it has today. It was Conservative and Liberal. But he never - he never mentioned what he did politically about it. No, no, he never - I don't think he - he bothered much - he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, mother - mother wouldn't bother at all. My father might say oh well I like so - the candidate so and such you see but he wouldn't say he was going to vote for him he just went along - and kept that to himself kind of thing - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Do you remember your parents ever talking about any issues or if they had any views about who should govern the country or if they felt the working man had a square deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, because in those days trade unionism hadn't the grip as it has - there was no - no trade unions or if there were they were only beginning - I remember quite - talking in the office about - any one that - that indulged in politics in trade
 union activities they were looked down on and if possible they - they'd find an excuse - oh yes, they were very - well they were very severs over any people dabbling in Labour politics, you see, because Labour as a rule were out for better conditions for
 
the workers and of course while the - the people working for - whoever it was - the people were working for they didn't want any disruption and consequently the - anybody ever started - or interfered in any way or talked politically about they would do th
is, that and the other they just - empty them out. 'Course there was a lot of unemployment and of course - it was - very easy to get - oh yes, easy to get labour. Yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So you kept your mouth shut?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right. Yes, you didn't 
mention anything. But people accepted everything. See - what would it be - a working man would get between eighteen shillings and twenty-five shillings a week and was able to keep a family on it and people were - although they had to, we'll say struggle a
 
little bit - I think people happier in those days than they are today. People nowadays have a car and that's the first thing they - they - they think about - well, I suppose, a year or two ago they did think about buying a house but nowadays I think the f
irst thing is a car and then of course another thing, in our day mothers didn't go out to work. You - you - you'd never find a - a mother going out to work. Now it's the thing. When - when a couple get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 
Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  they get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  with the idea of the wife goin
g out - yes. Oh yes. Both of them earn - yes, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Things are very different aren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember your parents voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, they would go, oh yes, oh yes, they'd go and - they'd vote - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But you don't know what party they voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, no. They might have a - a certain learning towards Conservative party because in the main they were people that were known anyhow but of course - it wouldn't be certain but of co
urse in those days there were Conservative and Liberal - the Labour wasn't - weren't - no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their jobs or their house if they voted differently from their employers - do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, because - he worked for a corporation and they didn't interfere in any way in their political lives. Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You don't remember him working for any of the parties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, he didn'
t take any active interest. Mind you, he was a great Irish man and he belonged to - what was then a Gaelic League but - it was more for social and to meet Irish friends that he got - nothing political - no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 
You mentioned you entertained a lot when you were a boy - you had a lot of people in, in the evenings.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right - yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would this be the pattern of their lives or would they do anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, they wouldn't - there was no outside entertainment until after my father died. The Hippodrome started to - to come into vogue you see and we - but no they didn't - not - nothing outside the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother have any interests at all outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. I wouldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she belong to anything in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, there were no - in those days - nowadays they have the union Catholic or Catholic Women's League - but in our days there wasn't - no. Sometimes on Sunday even
ing had - we called them magic lantern shows - nowadays the transparencies and very often we'd have someone come - to speak about their travels - probably a missionary from Africa or from one of the - one of the colonies. And illustrate with slides. And t
h
en very often we had concerts on a Sunday evening at the church - I'd forgotten about that. We had the concert - very often we had church hall and they'd get concerts up for different things you know, of course a lot of - some of the money would go toward
s the building of the schools because at that time the schools weren't as well off as they are - that's right, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your mother occasionally go to these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right, they would oh yes. And we had sales of work and - we had whist drives and - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did she ever go to those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh, well, occasionally but she wasn't - particularly interested - she was more - we'll say with being I suppose of Irish stock and home - a home bird - she was more set so I - I think she
 was alive today and there were bingo halls she wouldn't go to bingo.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
When she went out did she go out on her own to enjoy herself or if she went to the concert or the whist drive would your father go with her too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, we'd go together as a family. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When did your father get home from work in the evenings - you told me he did shift work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes. That's right. Well, with being a senior man he was more or less finished at six in the evening - six or seven - but he always automatic
ally polished shoes. I always remember - well they were boots in those days - people - there wasn't the shoes as we have them today - but he always polished his boots and looked after his clothing and they had a uniform - they always kept it clean. He'd d
o that in the evenings - yes. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He did it as soon as he came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, he'd have his meal and then later on he'd go and get ready for the next day. And probably get in a chair and - he'd read the evening paper but he - he wasn't a person that went out a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he ever go out at all on his own in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I can't say I ever remember him going. If - he - say we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Any pubs or clubs that he went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, he liked a drink but I think he more or less met people at - maybe - when he was working or on a Sunday but - he wasn't a great -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He didn't go out to the pub in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No - he liked to back a horse sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would he bet on horses regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I think he did fairly occasionally. Not - not regularly. O
r if he fancied - if somebody gave him a tip as they did in the old days and he fancied it he'd have a - but he never said - I think he was fairly lucky but he was very generous. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 
I remember him saying on one occasion - I think it was at the Pierhead and a 
man came up to him - of course you got a lot of people - they'd know you're of Irish stock I suppose by your looks - and they come up tell the story about - not having a meal Of course some of them were genuine. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And he - he was very generous fellow - oh yes, he was a very generous disposition - oh yes, if he had it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 
In fact he'd give us - 'cos he always said if I give anything, lad, I'd always get it back a hundredfold. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Strange wasn't it. Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did he ever }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 go to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, just - 
they had - 'course there were the illegal runners in those days. Or they had someone - yes, or - you know, probably couple chaps come in they'd probably put a - 'course they didn't - was like a bob I suppose - a bob and of course it was quite a lot in tho
se days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs like a boot or sick or funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, I'll tell you what we had up to the church we had a Catholic Bene - a - a Catholic Society - burial society and I think it was a case of cop
pers. 'Course in those - in our day a funeral - well, it cost about ten or twelve pounds - of course - money of course wasn't as - different to - and so we had this and - we had one of - a chappie from the church came - it was done more or less through th
e
 church - they had the office in the church - near - quite near to the church and we used to pay coppers into it. And rather strange - I paid into it - oh well, my mother - mother or father - I think it was a copper a week and just recently - only two or 
t
hree years ago, it wound up and we - they had quite a number of securities and unfortunately by the time - I've got some now unless I've destroyed them - somewhere about the house - they sold them, you know how it is when you liquidate - getting in touch 
w
ith people and I think the expense of - covering every - sorting it all out meant that all their - they had some very good - shares in different things like Mersey Docks and Harbour Board and few things - they all went, and I think we were paid out about 
- I think I got about nine or ten pounds out of it - somewhere about the average you got if they paid out but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But if you died you got this money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It covered for that - that's right, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you get on with your brother and sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, a family I suppose we had our own interests, in other words, we had our own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 chums}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
. We didn't - play a lot together I don't think except occasionally - just quite - quite close to - to us there one of the boys lived and he generally managed to
 get a little cricket team or a football - just amongst ourselves and there was a very wide unmade passageway at - it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 intended}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  to be a road but it wasn't made up and we used to meet there and put a big stone up for the wickets. They had a bat and get a
 ball from somewhere and we had very nice times there playing cricket - oh yes, cricket and football.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You would do this - not your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 My brother would come occasionally - that's right. But as he grew up he had a - more or less his own chums. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about your sister - did she ever join in with anything you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, my sister had her own friends. She would - school friends that she would go to and she -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Of the two who did you feel the closer to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Same with brother and sister. We had - didn't have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You didn't feel closer to one than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, I - I will say this - there was never - although we got on well and there was no bickering or anything like that - there wasn't great affection for some reason. 
I don't know why. I don't know why it was. Well probably my - in the case of my sister - being the - a girl you see and she was the youngest - younger one of the family and then my mother and my father - being a girl - being the only one - kind of played 
u
p to her and there might have been a - a touch of - kiddish jealousy amongst it. I put it down to that. But she had her own friends and except when she came out with us to visit - people - ordinarily - she'd have her own friends, yes. And my brother, I th
i
nk I told you, when he was about twelve he started - for some reason - he became friendly with this chap - the baker - Harbridge - with this chap and - he used to go there in the evenings and at night and - somehow - it might have been he was a great smok
e
r - it might have - buy cigarettes with the money. But I remember - I must tell you about one incident. When he was about probably thirteen, he wasn't very well - we were all fairly strong and our doctor was a Doctor Ivor Thomas, he was a very kindly man 
- of course in those days they rode a bicycle - there were no cars. And rather strangely he knew - the doctors knew every member of the family - they would probably bring you into the world and if he met you he'd say }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 hello}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Thomas, how's your dad or how's yo
ur mother? You see. Now, on this particular occasion - my brother wasn't well so - my father took him down to a local doctor, I don't know why - a man named - I remember - his name was Blackledge, he was a doctor in Prescot Road. I don't know why he took 
h
im to this chap - it might have been our doctor was off - away somewhere and he examined him. He said you know what's wrong with your boy don't you? So my father says no, that's why I've brought him along. He said well look at his fingers. And of course t
he nicotine. He said, it's smoking, he says it's smoking too much. I'll not say whether my father gave him a tanning to try to stop him but he - he didn't - no, he - no he always smoked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your father smoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He always smoked a pipe. And of cour
se for some reason in those days - they smoked pretty - pretty heavy stuff called a thick twist. You know sometimes I often remember - little things stand in your mind - sometimes, you know, if you have a little bit of a cold and you wipe your nose - you 
found this big handkerchief you could always smell the tobacco in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Apart from this open space where you said you sometimes played cricket, where else would you have played as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, the parks as a rule were some distance and - even chi
ldren became tired - they wouldn't bother to go - unless it was something special. Sometimes we'd have a cricket match. I remember when King Edward died - we had a day off at school and we went along to - one of the open spaces called - it - recreation gr
o
und and took our cricket gear down and - and in the middle of the game or just as we were getting interested policeman came along and chased us. We weren't allowed to play cricket on the - on the day of the funeral of the King. Oh yes. And all the shops h
ad black shutters or black shutter with awning round. What }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 you say}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 , it was a general holiday and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Nobody was expected to enjoy themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 To do anything - no, it was kept as - just like a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about the theatres and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 All closed - yes, far as I can remember. Yes, oh yes. I remember that quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Apart from cricket what other games did you play as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, peggy. You know what it is? Well you got a little piece of wood about - three or four inches lon
g and you'd chip the ends - just - chip the wood off the ends and made them just - a point. And then you had a stick about - a foot long and you'd hit the end and as the peg flew in the air you hit it, you see, and then one of the boys would say well how 
m
any will you do that in. Oh, it'll - paces, you see, oh, you do that in fifteen. Well, of course, if - if he did it well he took over the stick and the peg you see. And then another game we had was called ton weight heavy on. The boys would stand against 
t
he wall, say three in a line. One chap take a jump and jump on to the chaps back and of course if he fell down - if you shouted ton weight heavy on - he had to go all over again. It wasn't a hurtful - but it was just more or less fun. And the - the girls 
y
ou'd find - they used to make - what three, six nine - about nine squares and a little peg you know and they used to hop - play hopscotch. Old fashioned - heard of it have you? And, of course - if - in the season we'd get the - the - little pips out of th
e
 cherries - called them cherrywags. You go - you go up a - what they call up the spout - it was the spout of a house you know and throw - throw them up you see. Well if any came down they'd touched there were two or three rounds you swept those - they wer
e
 yours. Boys used to have a bagful of these - they called them cherrywags. And - what else was there. Oh - oh, of course in the wintertime snowballing - snowball - oh, and - little marbles, you don't see it now. There were a lot of marbles in those days, 
c
oloured marbles and then of course they had one other game which was three holes, you see, make three holes and you go from one to get it in. Well, if you didn't get it in the next boy'd go and knock - try and knock yours out, you see, and if he - if he d
id - got up and down so many times he won the game. With marbles. And of course there was other marbles as you threw and of course if another boy threw his and it hit yours he took your marble, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well of course you'd naturally you did get dirty and if you did when you got home you'd have to wash - wash your hands and face and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would your mother say anything or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh she said that. Oh no, I don't think - I think it was natural
 - unless you got very, very dirty she'd say - if it was very wet and you came in all muddy, that kind of thing, might be a bit annoyed but - I don't remember anything out the ordinary - no. We had to wash our hands and - and face and that if we'd been ou
t, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Pretty well, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember your parents ever discouraging you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I can't - no. Rather strange, I meant to speak about this yesterday, in our young days all the boys wore - skirts. Did you know that?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Up til what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
That was up to about four or five. Or - no, I'm sorry - up to about three because I think once you started school you were in trousers - short trouser
s, but you didn't have long trousers until you were leaving school. That was like - an event - you'd come to the age when you were to start - you - you went into long trousers. But up to school age - now in our age you joined - school started at three. We
 
started school at three. Oh yes, yes. Wasn't five. And every boy had lost his mother and father - and providing that he'd reached a certain standard of education they would let him leave school because some boys started work at thirteen. But - of course -
 
what shall I say - don't know whether they were stronger or what it - there was more work for young people but - a boy could generally get a job at thirteen. So some went into trades, you know, learn - apprentice engineering or apprentice joinery - appren
ticed to bricklaying. You see had to serve five years as an apprentice. But in the main most of these - the firms or I suppose the trade unions were just starting then - you'd have to serve - what you call serve your time which was five years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did the parents have to pay anything towards that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, but they - I don't think they paid the apprentice - he had - the parents had to keep the boy while he was learning his trade and then as he got on perhaps the second or third year, when he got a bit
 proficient they might give him a few shillings but in the main they didn't - didn't pay him at first - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you belong to any youth organisations - you said you belonged to the young }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, yes, yes, yes. But there didn't seem t
o be the youth organisations then that they have today. I must tell you this, with the children, of course you - there were all kinds of children you played with, you know, different churches and one of two of the boys go to a Band of Hope, they have - an
d
 so they - they said come along it's all right. So I of course - I should have told my father and mother I was going, but I went along to this and you had a little card and they stamped your card you know, with a little stamp for to show you'd been 'cours
e
 you kept that in your pocket and - every - everything was all right 'til Christmas came round and someone from the church came round to ask my father and mother did they want anything Christmas. You know, they gave vegetables and fruit and different thin
gs for Christmas - people were - there were - quite a lot of poverty. But of course my father was indignant about this and he wanted to know how it came about He said oh, the little boys comes to the Band of Hope.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did your father say about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well he said I should have - should have told them but they weren't too annoyed about it - no. Mind you, I suppose there wasn't the bigotry so much as you had latterly. I don't think so, no. You see, the people - the big fish started really with the O
range Lodges and they - I don't remember coming into - much - round where we lived it wasn't so much. You find it more in a section like the Everton section and the Scotland Road section and of course there was bitter trouble there - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember personally any friction between Catholics and Protestants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh I remember because my wife's fathers was a Sergeant in the Police at the time. And - he - just nearby was a church called St Johns Choobrook and it was very high church and the man a
t the time who was - pastor was pastor George Wise and he objected to this man who was supposed to be a member of the Church of England having high church practices like the Catholic church and consequently he would come along to Choobrook and bring hundr
e
ds of his followers with a couple of bands and someone would bring a table out and he'd stand on it and 'course they'd no loud speakers in those days - you know, they'd shout and - in some cases - there was always a chance they might raid the church so po
lice were - came on the scene and - kind of guarded the church so there was no - damage done - no. But there was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14109952\charrsid4933843 seeing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  any violence yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, spasmodic - people - windows broken and that but no - I don't remember anything really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 As a Catholic boy were you ever ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I was never involved in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you ever spoken to by any of these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no. No. It more or less - it was prevalent around Everton and of course, we just - didn't bother us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It depended on where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where you lived - that's right. So it - we didn't see much of it - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you have any hobbies when you were at school or did you keep any pets or did you collect anything? Or do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I can't 
- no, no gardening and - I think it was just like play and - nothing special, no, no. Latterly as school we had a woodwork class but then of course there was no provision at home - you didn't have a place where you could -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So you couldn't really continue it you mean?
