No, that's right, no. We had - father had a saw and a - and a ham - thing - he would do a little bit himself but he wouldn't like you to touch his things. No, no, because I suppose with children you might spoil them - that's right, t
hat's right. So there were - hobbies weren't - prevalent then as they are today you see, today a boy takes up stamp collecting or he'd have - might be painting or - woodwork and of course there's much more scope now than was in our day. That's right - its
 
just that - I suppose at the time there were hobbies and people were interested you might - but I think I mentioned that I was very friendly with the boy I - school chum of mine - Graham his father was a joiner, he used to make the different toys - yes, n
o
w that's another point. They had - occasionally they would have parties and with the Graham family lived an uncle, he was brother to the - to Mrs Graham and he was a great sport. He was a singer, but one of the old fashioned sort. And I remember the first
 
gramophone I heard - was the Edison Bell cylinder model and they had the big brass horn and of course in the party they put this on and they start off with - George Formby sing so-and-so, so-and-so - Edison Bell record - and then of course - have you ever
 
seen them? They're about - oh they're about this long, round and they went into a little cardboard box and people kept them in a kind of a holder, yes, and about forty records and of course it was great treat they took them - and rather strange on the - w
a
s the television just recently - it - it showed a film of Edison - the old Edison first started and how he started and this was one of his inventions - the gramophone, course it come - it was a wonderful thing - yes. And of course the same - then of cours
e
 the telephones and different things came in - they were - in - in those days it was the Bell telephone company. Now, of course it was nationalized afterwards - the National Telephone Company took it over but the Bell telephone people went over to Canada 
and I felt - I still think in Canada that Bell's name is still used, oh yes, yes.
