Well I think we more or less - father would help probably and - and probably a neighbour would come in and help because in those days I mean 
neighbours were more friendly than they are today and people mixed more. Now with us, we're here and we know all the people in the road but we don't mix. By that - we don't run up to a persons house. We meet them in the street - we'll chat with them and a
s
k them how they are and - if they're in any trouble you try and help them but you don't - we don't mix. No, no. But in our day the - the neighbours were more or less friendly. What - about four or five doors from us lived a family called Fitzpatricks and 
t
he father - was - employed at the corporation same as my own father and - I went - I was very friendly with the Fitzpatricks being close by and were - they were friendly. I - I - I remember going to the house one day and nursing Hughie and - he was only -
 he was younger perhaps - baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
