hat those boys were fourteen - they were - they had the potential - yes. They didn't get a chance - probably if - in our day there had been the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 opportunities}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  much more - more boys - university boys and that kind of thing, yes. Yes. My sister were only remar
king on that the other days that - in our own way we did quite well at this - we were never short of anything and - were able to hold our own with anyone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I suppose joiners and - 
people - engineer - people like doing the hard engineering side - working people. But - I don't remember us ever mixing with anyone of a higher status. We were very happy in this set we were in and we - as I say, as a family we kept more or less to oursel
ves so - wouldn't mix about very much. I think - more or less working class - people you met at church - meet them at church and as I said the concerts on a Sunday evening and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would these be roughly the same sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 People as ourselves 
- yes, yes, yes. One of the things - I - it struck me when - last evening when I was thinking over it - speaking about clothing. I remember Lewis's then was in a smaller way than it is today and my father would take us down to Lewis's and as you went in y
o
u'd get a chit and you'd go in, perhaps buy a suit of clothes - buy shirts, shoes, stockings and that. Well, as you - would - the different counters - whatever you bought they'd put it on this list and then it would go down to the delivery room - they wro
te it - delivered together, you see. A - a different system today. So that if you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So you could go round without carrying everything around with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Everything round - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You picked it up when you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's - well, you 
- they put it down what it was, as they do now, and then - someone as you leaving a commissionaire or someone took it and all the packages were put together and delivered to you at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, there was no snobbery. No, no. Not - not to be noticed. You might - people would know well - or they - like perhaps a bit a better plane than you are so you didn't - you wouldn't mix with them. But there was no -
 I don't think there was any snobbery - I think people more charitable in our days toward one another - much more charitable.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you ever told to touch your car or show respect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 To whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well to our teachers, we always - and to the clergy irrespective of what religion they were. Now, quite close was St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 Stanley - it was a Church of England church and the headmaster was a man named Deacon. They boys christened him, of course they shouldn't have - Billy D
eacon - but he was Mr Deacon and - the headmistress also at the school, I forget her name now, but if we met her or Mr Deacon or met the - the clergy of the diff - we always raised our hat and we were taught to do it and had to do it. Oh, it was very - oh
,
 it was expected - yes. I think the boys and girls in those days were more respectful than they are today. Its - its - it was - it was one of the things you did - it was tradition I'd say. If you met - another thing, if you met a person even thought they 
weren't the same as your own father - if you met them you always raised your hat or the mother - you always raised your hat to them - oh yes, that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember any particular persons that you called Sir or Madam or Master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well our teac
hers we called Sir or Miss but - and of course in the office - it was - if you spoke to anyone it was Sir. Oh yes, oh yes, you gave respect - more so than today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh, I think if the boys met my father or mother they would - raise their hat to them - oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 In the district where you lived who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I think the Vicars of the church had a lot - and - well I suppose there was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 fire people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 - the fire engine and the - the police and that kind of thing - but mostly the - the Ministers and the teachers. Were - that's right - yes, the people you kind of saw more or probably and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Why do you think they were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - I suppose - they were people of - to a certain extent - learning, put it that way. The people - a little bit above the ordinary because they taught you. Or in the case of the Ministers of the church because - he - education - respect 
- we respected them. I remember our Cannon saying that - at the time they had flower shows and near to us they had a West Derby flower show and all the people round about, including the - gentry - like - like the Earl of Sefton and probably Lord Derby wou
ld have - would have a stall and they'd have this show and - our Cannon - Cannon Hoare at the church nearby and the Cannon St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Stanly were all on the committee and one would be the Chairman another one the secretary, another one the treasurer. And the
y often joked about their congregations and I often remember - I think it was All Saints one of the churches - Cannon - it was a Cannon Hoare there, he used to say well, Cannon, to our Cannon, I've got a congregations of six - four thousand. So our Cannon
 would say, oh yes, but you've got two thousand of my people in that and they'd joke about it but - there was no animosity. Didn't have any counsel like they do today for the old -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who did the shopkeepers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I think they more or
 less - amongst themselves. They didn't - they had their own friends probably but - they were more - say the bakers, the - greengrocers, the ironmongers, the sweetshop - I think they more or less kept to themselves - they had their own little circle of fr
iends - yes. 'Course - we were known to them because of course we dealt from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would the clergy associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well the clergy always visited - there was more visiting in those days. Now, our Cannon knew everyone of the family - he would
 come in. But probably mostly because we helped at church and different ways. And - then - sometimes you'd have your own favourite one - a young curate might come along and he might be more of a favourite than the others - more of a mixer. And one of the 
y
oung - one of the curates was a Father Russell came to us - I would be - well, from an early age I served seven mass every morning - Hail Ronay - Hail Raymus nigh I went at seven. And through it I met quite a number of priests - different priests but - so
m
e of the older priests were more strict than our own. I remember one occasion, one of the priests on the altar forgot the host and he sent me into the Sacristy to get it and I knew where it was and of course I had respect for everything then, you wouldn't
 
touch it with your hand - you'd just shake one into the lid and take it on. I remember the - the priest in charge - the Senior Missioner coming - what are you doing, boy, what are you doing? And he was quite upset because he saw me doing this. And he - he
 took it out of my hands and took it on himself. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did he expect you to do though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, I suppose if I'd taken this on nothing would have been said but because he'd noticed me doing this he - he thought that - probably a boy - he didn'
t connect me particularly - but if any boy probably have the same respect as a - and it was kind of - it was something out of the ordinary you see and now - well now those kind of things are taken as natural - they think nothing of it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That sort of priest who was more severe - who would have been his friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well they were - they were orders and they'd go on missions to different churches and they'd come in contact with the Parish Priest and the - and of course the people - he'd visit the people that going to church. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would teachers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well they too - kind of mixed with themselves - they - they kept in their own little circle and of course they had teachers - club or society. They - they more or less m
ixed together. Yes, yes. And occasionally, rather strange, the teacher would come and visit the home sometimes. It might be if there were something on - if they were selling tickets for a concert or - something special on. We had sales of work in those da
y
s also. And if there was anything they'd come along to see if you were interested or have a ticket for it you see and then father might say, well how's my youngster getting on at school. Is he causing any trouble, do you ever have to thrash him - if you d
o
 let me know and I'll give him a - when he comes home. So - I think - I think in those days children were more - disciplined. Much more disciplined than today. And you expected - if a person told you a thing well, you wouldn't argue with them you see, but
 
now they'd - and you wouldn't - you wouldn't answer a person back because if they went - say they came along to - to my father and said well, your son answered he back, he'd give me a - he'd - threaten to thrash me you see. So of course we were - we respe
cted - we were brought up to respect others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would you think farmers and employers would have associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, there again, in their own circle I think. More or less their own circle. They didn't - they wouldn't mix with - say the worke
rs on the estate and that - they might have them on the estate but - in the main - round about Lancashire at harvest time they - they - most of them had - labourers from Ireland. Well those people come over and work here for all the harvest, they would ma
ke sufficient money here to go back to Ireland and live on that until the next harvest came along. Probably - yes, that's right - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about employers apart from farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well there again I think they had their own circle of friends. Oh
 yes, they wouldn't mix - there wasn't mixing the same - as there is today you see. 'Course - yes, nowadays - in an office they have - say - concert at the Philharmonic - they have special tickets you see - for that particular band of people and they go a
long to Philharmonic concerts and there's more social activities in that way than there was in our days. That's right - yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Where you lived in Old Swan did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say t
here were different groups?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well there was a lot of unemployment and I think a lot of the people had a hard time. In - Liverpool there were what they called pawn shops. You might have heard of them. And they had the three brass - regalia outside and
 people - if they were hard up - they would go along and pawn their clothes and - they'd get so much money on them then the end of the week when they got their wages and that they'd go and redeem them. Sometimes, it has been said I don't know whether it i
s so but it must - it must - people used to pawn their Sunday clothes and then get them out on a Saturday to wear. But there was more - I remember a particular incident - my wife recalled it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
There was a family that she - she was friendly with Choobrook and
 he was a customs officer - in quite a good standard and when my wife's brother left school - he went to this pawn brokers to I suppose learn the business and that and whilst he was in this lady happened to come in and she said to the man, she said, oh - 
I know that chappie - I don't like to come in and do business while he's here. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
So they moved him to another shop. And I think occasionally she used to buy - pawn different things you know, like a bicycle and that - anyone to know about it - yes, yes. But I 
don't know why though because - I suppose people sometimes would entertain and - in this - might entertain a bit above their - what they - their station you see - short - yes, that's - have to take it in you see. But you don't find it now do you - it's ve
ry seldom they use it buy amongst working class - I don't ever remember anyone in our family having anything to do with them but I know it was done. Oh yes, I know it was done, because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you think of any groups within the working class - whether there were certain standards that people had that were different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I think people kept more or less to themselves. Like more or less associated with - it wasn't the mixing about you see today. No. They kept their own selves - and I think, you see, 
more or less when people finished at the end of the day there was more home life than there is today there were no - there wasn't the attractions outside and they might have their own little circle of friends in business that would come and visit them and
 they'd visit them but in the main - that's the pattern of it, oh yes, yes. Wasn't the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, probably they did but it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 For what reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Because they thought they were 
a little bit better off - financially. But - people didn't take - they did or not. There might be a little bit of - no - there might be a little bit of leg-pulling about it you know or some joke - jocular remark about it but otherwise - people - so long a
s
 people had enough to go along with and look after themselves they didn't worry about anyone else. Today you see, you have this - you have this dustman strike here, now they managed to get three or four pound well everyone wants to be on the bandwagon to 
do the same and unfortunately you find people who are in the position that - we'll say }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 key men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 - can come out and demand what they like because if they don't get they throw hundreds of other people out of work. Well of course that didn't happen in the old days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
It is - I remember - yes, I remember the days - there was a strike - when it first started - the Labour started - first started I remember - on the tramways with my father was - but he wouldn't have anything to do with it and I think he - there was a 
bit of disfavour - he was very loyal. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
He didn't think - no matter what happened he didn't think - it was wrong to do that you see and I think at the time there was a little bit of - unpleasantness about it, they were on strike for two or three - they didn'
t get anything out of it - they had to go back again you see because they'd no - there was nothing strong behind them, you see, and so it was just the start of what we - what went afterwards - the trade union movement but they'd no backing, they'd no fund
s or anything else so that - and was no - if you were out of work you were out of work - you had to find - there was no such thing as going to the - to - the social security - there was no social }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 security}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 , you see, when my father died we all had to go out and - keep the home going. There was no - nothing to fall back on, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, yes, you'd get rough families. People of different -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How would you describe a rough family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I suppose people that didn't respect really - there were a lot of people - children in bare feet in my day and - probably worn clothes and - they might have spent their money on - might be drinkers, you see, there was quite a lot of people that w
ere - used to indulge in drink - go to the public house and that kind of thing. And the family would suffer and you'd find - oh this was quite - quite a common thing to see children in bare feet. And that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And this would constitute a rough family to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
To us, yes. Now what happened - the - police had a police aid society - I don't know where they got the money from, I think they got it from people who were generous and give them money - yes, and they used to buy corduroy suits and shoes for th
e - boys. But some of the children didn't like wearing them because - they had - it marked them as having - new corduroy. But there were - of course the reason why they bought that kind of clothing was they - it was hard wearing you see and in certain cas
es where they were pretty hard up they were glad to have them but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You mean the police would notice these children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right - they'd find out, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 They'd go round and offer the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, I think the police more or less k
new more about people than they do today. You see, if they were in an area they knew the people in the area because they mixed round - they were all in the same beat each day - they got to know the different families and when they knew there was genuine p
overty they would - or they might be recommended by the - one of the - one of the local clergy might say, oh such and such a family's not too well off and they'd try to help them that way, yes. And the church in some cases helped people too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 were in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  need?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember a distinction of this kind, rough and respectable, between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, there was always - see, a labourer was always a labourer - he was always a man to carry the tools for the craftsman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was he made to feel this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well he was - I wouldn't say he was made to feel it but he was kept - he wouldn't be allowed to do the craftsman's job. Although he could do it equally as well, in other words, if you were a labourer to
 a craftsman you traveled about with him everywhere and watched him do the job well the stage came that you could do it, perhaps in some cases, better than the craftsman because you're perhaps more adaptable to it. But you weren't allowed to do it, you se
e, the - the craftsman was always the better paid man from the working men. Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes - did they both share the same views about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I think they did - I - well
, mother was more of a home - bird and consequently she didn't worry about anything else - about - except the home. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 My father}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 was very respectful - he'd - he'd speak re - but he could hold his own. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Being an Irishman he was very jocular - he was known as be
ing - he wouldn't - he - he - he could say in a couple of words something very, very, very funny and he was very, very well liked for that reason, you know, they used to say oh he's very - he's and Irishman and he's very witty and of course people like th
at - it was natural it wasn't something that - that they learnt through education it just came natural to him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Natural wit. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No, she just - was for the home 
- she was in the home - that's right and went to church and - carried on just the same - just as a mother - there wasn't no - mixing about anywhere - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another and can you remember anybody who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I'll tell you what would happen. If you moved into a better house - better class house you might appear to be a stage higher - you understand what I mean - if you move from a smaller cottage to - a better class property, some people }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 would get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
on well in business and they'd move up a little bit in - in ; and mix with different people - but in the main there wasn't a lot of it. I don't remember a lot - no, no. See most of our life was bound round the church and consequently you accepted people 
as they were - people came that probably were - might be better off in life than you were but you accepted them - you respected them and - they respected you but there was no - no snobbery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You don't recall many people moving from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no, no. I wouldn't say that - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You do remember seeing policemen round where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did you think of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well as boys we always - called after them sometimes and sometimes they'd - hit you with their glov
es - wouldn't hurt you - no. And if you did anything wrong and they caught you they would just take you round out of sight and take their belt off and tan you, oh yes, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 knock}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  you and - but of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well we too
k it as - that it was - that it was right you see - oh, you accepted it. Oh, you wouldn't go home and tell your parents because it - oh they'd know - oh, they'd know very well that you were in the wrong because they wouldn't do go it unless you were doing
 - oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How do you think they treated people generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well they were - we'll say they were a policeman class, in other words they were - what shall I say - on their - own. They didn't - people didn't mix with them quite as they say -
 apart to a certain - because of their work. And I think they were - they were encouraged in that - in that, you see. My father - for obviously my wife's people were in the police - he was a policeman but you hadn't got to mix because at some time or - ot
her you might be involved and therefore you didn't - it wouldn't do to be involved with them because you mightn't like to do things that you'd have to do - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Can you remember your mother ever saying when you were naughty I'll call a policeman - did she ever use it as a threat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I don't think so. I believe it was done but not in our house - no, no. She'd call my dad probably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was your home rented when you were a lad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you see anything of your landlord?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes. He was a very nice gentleman. Yes. He owned quite a lot of the properties round about, he would always come in and have a chat and - he was a friend really and if anything wanted doing he'd have it done. Oh yes. We were very fortunate in that way.
 And sometimes at Christmas time he might give us sixpence, a shilling you know just a little present. Oh yes, he was very - he round to us very often. But rather strange, in Liverpool nearly all the landlords were Welsh people. Wales - }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Welsh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  people built 
Liverpool in many cases - they often say - well I think all this property round here was built by a man that came - originally came from Wales. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
I - you see, it's quite close to North Wales and people came in and it started off and built a chapel or it might be a - a bricklayer and he'd get a joiner and someone else;- he'd build a lot and of course the banks would loan them the money. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Now what happened in this area - the man who owned all - just this - what you'd call the older property here, was a man named
 Charles Berrington - the road is called that - Charles Berrington Road, now he owned all this property 1/2 Now in 1914 the bank called their money in and so consequently he - he had to sell all his properties to pay that bank back. So what he did, he cam
e
 round the houses here - now these houses were originally built for about two hundred and fifty pounds, now today they'll bring round about - if they're well cared for - they'll bring in two thousand five hundred and four thousand pounds. But of course we
 
must remember people in the meantime have had to do a lot to it and modernise and that kind of thing - improve them so of course - but in those days people here in this area would pay for a house like this eight and threepence a week. Now when Berrington 
h
ad - went into liquidation - he came round or he sent his agent round and said now if you put twenty pounds down and pay eight and six a week and your rates in twenty years the house is yours. That's what happened. That's why most of the people round abou
t have their own house. Now, in the case of this house, when I bought it from - is this - this story will carry on. When I bought his house I paid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  hundred and twenty-five pounds for it. That was 1924 - '24 - '25. Now the lady that was here had gas and 
she was a widow and she hadn't done much to the house so the first thing we did was to find someone to put the electric in. Now the chap we - through someone mentioning it to us that she knew someone what was out of work - he was an electrician and he was
 
a very good chap at his trade and he'd be only too pleased to come and do it so he came along and he gave us an estimate. I think to put electric in all the rooms including two or three points in the house - probably two points at the time - I think it wa
s
 eight pounds ten and that was a week's work. And he made a very good job of it - he did it all in pipes brought it in on pipes - that included materials and everything else. Well with getting our job he got another job and it put him on his feet. So we w
ere pleased about that, oh yes. Now as regards other things, gradually there was different things we wanted doing. We had next door to us the man who was the joiner for this property.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No never, never, no. They were - I rather - I will say sensible people. They - they just lived - they new what their income was and they lived according to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 And you were fairly comfortable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, oh yes, and always - yes, and always had a nice suit on and nice clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - no - he was never out of work - yes - - he but unfortunately with the - working for the - very often he was at
 the Pier Head - right in all the bad weather and consequently he - he - he contacted - bronchitis - might have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 been}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 his smoking - but - it is - - I found - probably they will tell you this that people who - who smoke - smoke a lot are inclined to be bronchial aren't the. Now, bronchial - he got asthma with it. Now I always remember, yes, I can remember it even as a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 youngster}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 - the - doctor from the corporation came along to see him - it was Professor McFall and he had a look at him and then our own doctor - - Doctor Blackford came along and they had a pow-wow as to the treatment they would give my dad. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Now they - I don't know what they did but he - he was really very sick man because he couldn't to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4933843  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
- he was propped up more or less - he couldn't lie down - now they gave him a pad of some kind and I always remember this - he'd got round his legs here just the calves of the legs like sponge and it was always discharging water. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Now it might have been a kind of a dropsical complaint but I don't know but I always remember that and that went on for couple - couple of -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was he out of work quite some time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh he was out - about three months he was ill - three or four months, Now, I remember gradually he - the people were very kind - there was one of the ch
aps coming in - I remember one chap coming in with a fiddle to play a fiddle. Oh that was another thing, we had - a great friend with Bretherton Reapers and my brother had - at the time - just this particular time - they had a violin class at the school a
n
d of course he joined it and they paid sixpence a week and that covered the lesson and the violin and one of the Bretherton Reapers - a Mr Vivian was very friendly - I don't know how - where my father came across him but he was a very musically - he could
 
play several instruments and he often came up to the house and entertained us and he'd give Willie lessons on a violin and my brother was quite good at it and had he - pursued it he would have mad a - an orchestral player but with going into Harbridges an
d
 - kind of his other things you know - he didn't - that's right - and he did keep it up until he was wounded in the war and then gradually he left it and he never bothered with it again. Oh, it's a pity really because he - one of the ladies - one of the y
o
ungsters at the school that was with him she had a little orchestra afterwards and - would have been - and they had little professional engagement - he could have done something with it but he - he was one of those hale hearty well met if he had five shil
lings in his pocket he'd spend it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When your father was ill like this how did you manage - what difference did it make to the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well I think - I have a feeling that he was in a kind of a - I suppose in those days they'd call a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 tontine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  which covered sickness - I think that's probably -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 This was a club he belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
That's right. If - in case of his employment - and when he was - when he was ill I think it covered him and then of course the - with working for the corporation I thi
nk they had their own doctor used to come and see him. And if you had brought a private doctor in you paid, I think in those days probably be half a crown or three shillings, something like that at - you paid him as he came you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So did you not notice any difference at all in your life when he was out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well we were sad - oh no, no, we - he was able to - he was able to - oh yes, we were able to continue as we were, yes. Mind you, I suppose us youngsters you don't notice things as you wo
uld had you grown up but - yes, but we never - we weren't short of anything - don't remember being short of anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you ever get help from the Guardians or the parish or any charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Never. Never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When there was someone in the dis
trict who the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it - do you remember anyone being made to leave by rough music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, no, no. The only thing that probably - on of the things I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 dodo}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  - I do remember someone in the road they'd been away for the in the Seminary for the Priesthood, this boy came - this chappie came out and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  and he died very young and people used to say, oh well, he shouldn't have - shouldn't have left - he should have carried on kind of
 thing. Nowadays that would be taken for granted, they'd think nothing of it. In our days it - it was thought - yes, they didn't think it was right. But if - if he went - if he did that he would be - he should have continued. But latterly of course one of
 
my friends went away and he was away for two or three years - up until 1914 well when he - of course the war came along and through the war he came out but that was nothing thought - of it then you see. People are getting - with war people - ideas changed
 - yes, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No. No, straight to school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How old were you when you started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Start at three - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When you first started did you - just go for the morning or the whole day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, the whole of the day - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What time did you start in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Nine. Nine 'til twelve - one thirty to four. That's it - it was a full day for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 infants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  and grown ups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 An infants school - taught by - the Nuns and the teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, it was a church school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Catholic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you get to school and how long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 We walked to school - about ten minutes walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Who would have taken you when you were three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, I think it was - generally round about were children used to go and we used to go together. And there wasn't the traffic on the road there is today so consequen
tly we had no anxiety and we walked - we more or less find our way. Mind you, when we were very small we may have been taken but once we got to school and what we chummed in with children and go to school - but there was no worry about crossing roads beca
use it was horse traffic and - nobody bothered. No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You had your mid-day meal at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 At home, that's right - went home for dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did you think of school - did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - I managed to keep up with
 everyone - I wasn't brilliant but at the same time they termed me a plodder so I - it didn't - didn't worry me at all - I managed to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  on and each class - I left once class to go into the other at the end of the year and - I was never kept back in anyway - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What did you think about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, being - being church school they were people we knew also at church and we got well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were they mainly religious or did they have a lot of lay teachers as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But they were all lay
 teachers - oh yes, yes, and rather strange I don't - we never had a Headmaster - they were all lady teachers taught me. Yes, I never had - no male teachers at all - no, no. And they were good teachers too. No, all my school life they - the first - the fi
rst Headmaster we had was after I left school we had a man named Dan Hayes but in my day it was a Miss Devlin and she was a very strict, very clever very smart and very, very well thought of. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life - such as manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Punctuality and ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well not so much ways of speaking but - they'd pull you up if you didn't speak correctly. And of course you was taught reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh manners, oh yes, very particular about that. Oh yes, tidiness, oh yes they liked to - yes, oh yes. The boys generally at school had collars you know they were quite -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Quite neat and tidy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh, they were very keen about being at school at nine - - the gates were closed at nine o'clock and if you weren't there you had to go home - you couldn't get in. And of course there were - in those days they had men would come round if you weren
't at school and if - if you were so many attendances, say - people used to - an expression the boys used to call I don't know if it's - heard today - used to say, their playing sag. I - don't know where the expression came - its sag, yes, sag, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  it sounded like that - like sag. Well it meant playing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 truant}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 yes, and then if a boy did that they'd give him - they'd tell him if you aren't at school on such and such a day you'll be taken away. They took him to what they called a truant school at High Town and 
they'd take them away for two or three weeks - kind of like on the same lines as an approved school and they were taken away if they didn't - they were very strict on that too - more so than to - I think, today. Very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 They would give them a rough time would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well the boys didn't like going but I suppose it was more because they were away from their parents - they'd get their food and that. I don't know what the conditions were - whether the parents would have to give something towards
 it, but I don't think so but - if the boys was - if he didn't attend school he was - they called it the truant school and I always remember it being at - High Town - that's on the way to Southport, of course, yes. Liverpool slang.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, they would cane you. They had a cane and you got six strokes on your hand. You had to hold your hand out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you caned in front of the class or did you have to go and receive this punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh no, no. We were caned in front of the class - except for something exceptional when the head teacher would come in - everyone was caned in front of the class - nobody caned outside it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What - would you be punished for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well if you w
ere very naughty and you wouldn't pay attention and sometimes boys playing tricks - if you were caught playing tricks or for instance I remember one time the boys were caught playing football in the classroom. All the boys - I should have been one of them
 but I was a monitor so - I always felt guilty afterwards but I know they all got six in front of the school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was it a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No they were separate. We were all boys, yes, yes. The boys school and the girls school. Yes,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, they would ask the teachers how we were getting on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did they ever visit the school or meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well occasionally if there was - a schoolday - but it wasn't very often, not like they have nowadays. No. Wasn't regular thing, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Not necessarily, they'd know from the teachers if we weren't too good the teachers would send a note home - and we'd have to take a note home and that'd say and then of course your father would have - father then was the one that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He'd say now you've got to start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes. Yes, yes. But I don't think - we enjoyed school - we were regular at school and it - with that you kind of kept up with everything and
 nothing was - wasn't really an effort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did the other children - come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, pretty well, yes. There may be one or two just a little bit - perhaps better off than we were but the more or less - with the g
rammar school - weren't so many - there weren't so many convent schools in those days so that - only exceptional their parents could afford it would send their children there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the rest?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, of course we would say oh Miss so and so has her favourites but in the main they would try not to show it. Yes. I suppose if a boy - somebody like myself that the teacher took a liking to you, might say, oh Tommy will you - O I would l
ike you to take a message for me you see and I suppose the boys and that and - and on them, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were there any gangs or - groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well there were little - not - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 rough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  gangs. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 We had our little party - we called it a gang - in the playground that played together - three or four boys in a little group would play together.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you keep to these groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, to play. But after school, unless you - we might chum in - - one or two of the boys we had at school might chum 
in at their homes but there was no gangs outside the school. Oh no, no rough or anything like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you go onto another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I was at the one school all the time - right up to finishing - fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You left school when you were fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Fourteen - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well no, because there was nothing more they could teach me at that particular school, you see, in other works I didn't get a chanc
e I wasn't brilliant, which you had to be to get - had to be brilliant and of course we weren't brilliant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, you wanted to tell me about the books?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, recap about the books. At school I would be - of course with starting school at three by 
the time we were six we could read pretty well, six to seven. And ten the South-African war was just finished - just finished so we had - with the library being close by - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Carnegie}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Library - we borrowed books on South Africa and all about the war and a
bout Kruger and Lord Roberts and all the people that were concerned and - for some years we read the books and were most interesting. So much so that we felt we'd like to go out to South Africa. Yes, it does .. Now, just another little point that I'd like
 
to speak about - you're asking about hobbies. Now, it came to mind that I used to collect match boxes and match sticks and Robinson - Crusoe we had at school and consequently we used to try and make a little village like Robinson Crusoe had - yes, with th
e
 matchboxes and the sticks and different things and then - of course - at the time you could buy little clockwork - trains and sets - I think they were about a shilling prone and six and we had those at home too. Of course also we had the games like draug
hts, dominoes, ludo, snakes and ladders and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 games. Oh yes, so we had quite a selection so, taking it all round we were quite happy at home, yes, oh yes, we had something to do. And then of course in the summer evenings you'd play and take it on
 this - this - on Main Road there which is quite good - the surface was very good for playing and then with - later on when I was about - twelve - eleven - twelve - I came across the Graham family. The father was a joiner - he used to - make these lovely 
k
ites and always had something - special and he was a really lovely chap. Real family they were real lovely - I think they were - the mother was - might have been Scotch but the were really lovely people, but it was very nice and with coming in with them o
f course that used to pass quite a lot of the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 He was the one with the bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 asked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 you if you would have stayed longer at school if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, well I suppose to a certain extent unless you'd got a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 career}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 in view - in our day there was no - not the same chance of going to University or going in for higher education and therefore if you missed a grammar school at eleven or twelve - you were kind of out of the running then - they wouldn't - they
 weren't interested. You see, I had to be around the twelve mark to go to a grammar school and then you'd probably stay 'til fifteen or sixteen then I think I mentioned that when I left school I went to - one of the local evening classes, yes, I did - com
mercial course. I had - Lexington Cheshire Watch certificate for something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How long would you have attended this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 About two years I - yes. About twice a week I thin, yes, yes. That was in the evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What sort of things were you doing in this - commercial course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Just rubbing up arithmetic and - composition and English and subjects we'd had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 at}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  school - kind of polishing it up, yes, that's right. Composition and English
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 No, I do
n't think so because I found that in business no matter what I was called upon to do - once I got the hang of it, it was no trouble and the same applied to all the family - my sister were only saying - saying the other days that both she and our brother a
t our particular job we did very well. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 In fact, had it not been that we had to wait for people dying we would probably have become much better than what we did, yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 While you were at school did you have a part time mob - you did, you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Just on the Saturday - that's right - Just the Saturday helped really to keep me out of mischief. That's what he used to say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You saw boy wanted in the window didn't you or did you get it some other way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I think they were always
 - you could always pick up a job - I'd have probably heard someone say they wanted a boy and I - but in those days they were always glad of a boy to take errands - to run errands at Saturday, yes, the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 This is what you did - take errands out - this is all - you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, that's right - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Pack them up into boxes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Yes, well they'd make it up - in the shop - take them out to the different houses. Like an errand boy I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How many hours did you work on the Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I think about eight to eight - a long day, yes, yes. But of course being a youngster you wouldn't notice it and - there was no trades unions in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You wouldn't have had any holidays while you were doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - holiday time - oh yes, I'd go over to Ireland for my holidays, oh yes I would - wouldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Would they pay you for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, the wouldn't - oh no, no, it was just while you worked you were paid, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You got a shilling for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you feel that was a fair wage at the time or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I - I suppose it was the average you couldn't get anything more and - a shilling was quite a lot in those days - you could have a - a day out for a shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
No, I think - I gave it to 1 for some reason I don't know why I gave it to my dad but it come up - it all went in the house - to help in the house. Because my father was very generous in everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you get on with the people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh very well because in those days you had to be - it was more - people were more civil and boys were more respectful than they are today. If you were told to do a thing you did it kind of thing and I suppose you 
liked the job and you didn't want to upset anyone and then of course - yes, oh yes, and I think I got - seemed to have a manner in those days seemed to - please people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh pretty well. But - you always felt that - just toed the line sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Were you conscious of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, I think so, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you resent this at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, because I'd always been - used to - used to it, I mean at school the discipline was strict, if you didn't ob
ey you got the cane and of course consequently I suppose when you came to do anything for business or anything like that you kind of take it as - that's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you feel about the work - did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I found it - 
sometimes I felt it tiring you see - physically yes, yes, and - sometimes you say oh, I'll give it up but - as it's only once a week you didn't bother so much, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did getting the Saturday job alter your attitude to school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I don't think so. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 I'd like to ask about your first full time job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, my - I was offered a couple of jobs but my father was keen on all the family going into something that - where there's a pension attached to it for after life. I was - at the 
time I wasn't very happy about it because I - I was offered a little job I thought would have been - I would have liked that. Yes, I was offered - to start off film was just starting then and - there happened to be a family attended the church who were fi
lm renters or starting in the film renters business and they had a - they had an office in Pembroke Place just starting and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 father}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Russell who was a great friend of mine in church said, Tommy if you start with them you start at the bottom and you'll lea
rn the business right through. But my dad didn't think that - he thought it was just the - in those days they called them the flickers - it was just cinematascope flicking on the screen and - being Irish I suppose he thought there was no backing to it, th
at it would be just something that comes today and is gone tomorrow - so into the Post Office I - I - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you get into the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - I had to attend at this establishment branch of the Post Office in - Victoria Street in town - 
I think I went down with two - two or three boys. We had an interview.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you apply - did your parents arrange it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 No, I think I went myself for it - yes - and you had a - an - an interview - and then I think we had a slight test as to what
 we could do - then when they found that we were suitable we received - I always remember a mac, a belt and - pouch I think it was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
That was the start of my career as a boy and that was - November 1910, yes, this -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What exactly did you have to do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
In the - oh, well I was - I started off as a messenger boy. In those days we had about - in Liverpool - six hundred - six hundred or six hundred and fifty boy messengers. Their job was to take telegrams out. The telephone wasn't as efficient
 as it is today consequently there were tremendous amount of - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 telegraph}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 service was very busy - especially in the - for business people in the town and also for - the districts. So I started at a little office in Choobrook - a little sub Post Office a
nd there were three boys there, we had - a split duty starting at eight, we worked nine hours - eight in the morning to eight at night with a split in the middle of the day. We had a bicycle to take distant messages on - I was there from - November up to 
a
bout the following - August or September 1911. And then we were - boys then after so much - so much - so many months at the sub office had to go down to the head office in Victoria Street. Well there there were about - oh, four or five - at least three or
 four hundred boys. When we attended there we were told we would have to do an hours drill every day until we were proficient and we - there was no pay for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 , you just did that as part of your - yes. We started off with - foot drill - marching - take our coats off and just - trousers and shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you enjoy it or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well I - I didn't mind it you see. There again - with being at school - and of course the thing was - boys were keen to get the job - quite a number of boys out of work even in t
hose days and consequently we liked the job, we knew very well if we didn't do as we were told well - we - we'd be out and it might be difficult to get another job so of course we took it as such. Now we did eight - mostly eight to nine if you're on at ni
ne in the morning, or if you're on early - say there were boys on at seven you'd have to have a break and do your hours drill in the morning and - the hour you did at the drill wasn't considered part of your duty - in other words you had to do it -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 It was extra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Oh had to do that extra you see. Now - in addition to marching and - different things - saluting - we had - taught saluting we had about - twenty-four carbines and we did carbine drill - sloping arms, presenting arms marching with arms an
d everything else. We did - on the - in the office - they also had a rifle range but at the time as we were boys we didn't do much at it. Later on if you wished you could go on the miniature - it was a miniature rifle range - quite a number of boys took a
n interest - I wasn't sufficiently interested in that. But - you - you had to do this hour until you were passed out as proficient.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How long would that have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, perhaps a month or two, then after that you were all right providing you didn
't - get into trouble in - we had to salute five different people in there belonging to - the heads of the post office we met - met them in the - as we were passing each other along the road or the street. And if one of them - if you didn't salute - we ha
d
 our number at the side on our collar you see and they noticed the number you were reported - they reported it when you get back. And you filled - have to go up again for another course of drill until - oh yes, oh yes, discipline was - discipline was very
 
strict. Now, every day as we went on duty we used to form - up - we were checked, our boots were checked, buttons and belt - clothing, haircut and everything, just like a soldier, we did that every day. Now, if a boy wasn't up to scratch they'd send him h
o
me, tell him to get his hair cut or buttons cleaned or boots or shoes polished. But they were very - the discipline was very keen and if you - had to ask a question, there were assistant inspectors in charge of the floor you'd have to go up and salute and
 
ask the question you see, and then salute before you came away. We were just like little soldiers. Mind you, I don't - I never objected to it. But we had nicknames for all the different - inspectors. And one chap I remember was very like, in those days, S
e
xton Blake stories were all the go you know and he - this chap was one of these quiet chappies, didn't give much away and we - he got the name of Sexton Blake. But - even with boys - always certain amount of fun - certain amount of mischief, Now after I'd
 
been there say about - oh six or eight months they had boys on - working in the offices, that is doing the - answering the phone, running messages, taking documents from one place to another and - I rather thought I'd like this so - I did a spell of that.
 
The only difference was that - on the - when we were at head office we were on what they called the docket - you were - you had twenty messages for a shilling, you were paid by the number of messages - messages you delivered you see, so the idea of that w
a
s to - I suppose so you would be quick over - over them but sometimes you'd be unlucky, you might be there all day. The first message you got would be for the North Western Hotel you'd come back and get the Adelphi Hotel and probably get the Waterloo Dock
.
 You might have a day like that when - you'd struggle all day - for nine hours - to get twenty messages in. And then in the summertime - for some reason went quite busy and consequently - you'd have a job sometimes. And then, another point - if the place 
w
as quiet and they had too many boys on - they would let - providing you had so many messages in at that particular time they'd let you off - before you'd completed the eight or nine hours - oh yes, that's more for their own convenience. But against that w
as the face one of the duties we had was - ten one - ten to one - three eight to nine. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
Now the idea of the three eight was for every hour you worked after eight o'clock at night, instead of working the hour you worked fifty-two minutes - you got eight minut
es night allowance, oh yes, eight minutes - there was no extra pay but it was - night allowance of eight minutes so if you worked the night duty you would work seven hours instead of eight - that is later on when you came onto the eight hour day but that 
was quite some time afterwards. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 But - that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How long would that have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well - got onto that round about 1913 I came onto that - 1913 - 1914. But - on this - on the duties docket - we were on the docket - once you went up onto a - an - a - as
sistant in the writing rooms there - you did - your week commenced on the Wednesday To the following Thursday so that if you - broke from - one - the dockets onto the writing rooms sometimes you'd only get a half a week in and - but - but somehow I don't 
m
other never complained - we always seemed to manage all right - we were happy at home - they just - Now I remember at the time telephone were - weren't as - prevalent as they are today. I remember going up to the engineers to work with the engineering bra
n
ch you see and they - and one of the men said to me - have you ever used the telephone sonny? And I said no. He said - well you'd better get onto it. You know, it was the turn - you turned the handle you see then lift the receiver and speak into it so - h
e
 said, get onto Edgworth station. Of course you'd never get Edgworth station because there were so many people ringing up Edworth station but it - it gave you - you could ring up different places you know. Just ask a silly question just to get into the id
e
a of answering the telephone. And that was one of the duties we did. And then of course you - you took papers from one place to another. I remember one of the duties we had to - take papers into the Head Post Master who in those - well - he was Post Maste
r
 surveyor in those days - he was a man named Salisbury - quite a big noise and I remember he'd ring the bell and as he rang the bell you'd go in and he'd say - let's have a look at your hands. And the next boy had to - I don't know how these - soil marks 
g
et on the papers. He was seeing if your hands were clean for when you took the - the documents. 'Cos in those days London did all the - the Secretary's office in London did all the - most of the - what shall I say - answered all the - any difficulties - a
n
y - any queries - in the big way - the document went to London in a pouch every night so the pouch would be made up and we used to take it down to London Road and they would - we'd see it in the London bag so that it would arrive there for next morning, y
o
u see, and they in turn - the pouch would come into Liverpool and if there were one or two they were booked in - all the pouches were booked in and booked out so they knew what happened to them, oh yes. Now of course official papers were all numbered such
 
as one-oh-eight-four-seven stroke three nine, it was three nine, whatever it was - the year - stroke - so that if any ; thing happened to the papers they were booked into Liverpool and were booked out to Liverpool and where the papers were sent so if - an
y
 papers sometimes probably queried by someone in London in rather a high position they would come up, now with - what they call an M.P. case, if an M.P. raised the matter in the house it became a red flag case. And I believe it still continues today. A re
d
 flag case when it came to Liverpool had to be booked in right away with the number and the Head Post Master took charge of it right away and the - the question, whatever was raised - London should - was supposed to have the answer within forty-eight hour
s - sometimes it'd take three days but - very, very important, red flag case when it came up - came - yes, red flag on it you see and that was - everyone that handled that had to - be on their toes. But they were interesting days - yes, oh yes. Yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you go into the office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well, I'll tell you what happened. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
When we were thir - when we were sixteen - about sixteen - sixteen and a half, we had to sit a Civil Service exam - and then from that we were - had - four, I think it was four jobs offered us to go on the postman\rquote 
s side, to go into the customs as a water guard, to go into the army as telegraphist or to go into the Navy as telegraphists in which case we would come back as telegraphists in the - in the office. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 You see, come back on the - mor
e or less on the clerical side. And of course I didn't want to leave home but I did think of taking water guard in the customs which we - which I thought at the time was suitable but I think they offered me Cardiff and it would have meant me leaving home 
so I said no I'd go on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 postman\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 side. So from Head Office I went to the Northern District Office. Now, there's a rank in those days called assistant postman - you did a six hour day - - thirty' six hour week and the idea was you took post and that of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 postman\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 walk they call it - his area that he delivers they call that a walk - you take a portion of that so that every delivery in the town was finished by half past eight. Every - everything had to be finished at half past eight. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Now - there was coll
ection I think, if I remember rightly, at half past eight, twelve, four, six, eight, and then there's a midnight collection at night so that there were very - almost every two or three hours was collection of letters and with a collection, deliveries coin
cided more or less. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
There was a delivery at seven, there was one at ten, one at twelve - one at four and one at six. Every day, yes, yes, oh yes, oh yes, oh yes, yes. Seven, ten, twelve, four, six and eight - deliveries of letters in those days. So that you
 - I remember - we only just discussing this a little while ago - you could post a postcard - when I - the time I was - in the office - say 1910 - 1911 1 with a half penny stamp on it in Liverpool at eight o'clock in the morning - it would be delivered in
 
London between four or six in the evening. You could reply again on a half penny postcard, post it in London and it would be delivered in Liverpool next day and that was - that was - they were very strict about that. When I first started in the office as 
a
 postman every letter was back stamped. Not only had it the time it was posted but as the mail came into Liverpool each man had so many bags to handle they had to back stamp all those letter with the time it arrived in Liverpool so a person could see what
 time the letter was posted and what time it was delivered, but later on they knocked that on the head and - in the interest of economy, of course economist said economy, they knocked it on the head. But that was the rule.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Thirty-six hours - what did you get paid for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Fifteen - fifteen shillings and ninepence - fifteen shillings and ninepence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What was a full }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 postman\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Eighteen shillings at eighteen. Eighteen shillings, yes, that's right. Now it was age pay - at eighteen shil
l - at eighteen, eighteen shillings and nineteen nineteen, at twenty a pound and in addition we had a boot allowance, I think it was about a guinea a year - ten and six a half year - for your shoes. But in later years they incorporated that into - pay div
ision that they had and that was lost - oh that was - that was lost you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How much money did you get when you first started when you were fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Five shillings. Five shillings - yes, five shillings to six shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Why was there a difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well, as - as you progressed, you see, I think it was more of an age pay. Round about sixteen - fifteen to sixteen get to six shillings, yes. And sometimes there was a little bit of overtime - not very much - and I think the overtime rate wa
s round about tuppence ha'penny an hour. Mind you in those days you could have a - a - you could go say from town up to the Olympia I think a penny on the trams - the Echo was a ha'penny, you could get a seat in the gods for tuppence or fourpence in the b
a
l - balcony, very, quite a good seat, and there were very good artists in those days - you - you could have - you had a cup of tea and a sandwich - when you came out - probably something to eat bus - your tram fare home and still have a couple of coppers 
left out of a shilling. People don't think about those days. I think everyone would be happier - people would were happy in those days although there were a lot of poor people I suppose. Yes, oh it is, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you give any of this five shillings to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes, I think I did. And then, I think I gave her the money and then she gave me - pocket money out of it and tram fares and we had might be coppers - you'd get a - perhaps a cake for a penny and - I'm not sure - I think even a cup of 
tea was round about a ha'penny in those days. But - we'd have enough really. Sometimes of course you'd get a tip from the people - you took a telegram they might give you a tip and - the - it all made - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did your immediate employer treat you when you first started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well they were very strict, everything was strict. If - if you did anything wrong you had - you - you were taken up before the Chief Inspector and you had to salute him and he told you - he asked you to explain why you did
 this certain thing. Now in the Civil Service I think the same applies to all Civil Servants, even down to the lowest grades, they didn't actually tackle you - they gave you a paper asking you why you did it. They call them form eighteens, we always used 
t
o have form eighteen day - on such and such a day you were observed to do so and so - please say why you are - say why you this, and then you would put your reply on it. Well of course the heads took it down and he read it and then he put - his comment on
 
it and it'd go to someone else and go ' eventually it'd finish up at the hierarchy and say well I think this person, this boy did the wrong thing, he should be punished with two hours extra duty. And so that - we had to do two hours extra duty. In other w
ords you'd did two hours and you wouldn't get any pay for it. Oh yes. But of course in the main we -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well we didn't feel it as an - injustice because - unless - if you thought you were badly treated you could appeal 
against it and can go - oh yes, there was always someone to appeal to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did you like or dislike the work generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well - the - the - I found the work in the town delivering and that rather }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 
heavy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  because we - we were like soldiers we had to wear
 - short - we had short leggings ; leather leggings we had to wear in addition to our shoes. Now, if it was a bad day the instruction was you must wear your leg - leggings and going about the town all day tramping round with the heavy shoes and that at - 
s
ometimes you'd feel very weary and that time I used to be very, very weary - oh yes, but it was part of the - like a soldier, part of the duty - so of course you - you couldn't take your leggings off because if you did you were - on the carpet, yes, oh ye
s.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Did the full time job alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 No, I don't think so, no. You took it just as part of the span of life, you know, the - yes, that's right, that's right, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What jobs have you done since the first world war - you've stayed with the Post Office haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Yes, well, what happened was this, on the - fourth of August 1914 war broke out. The - senior - many of the men were reservists in the Army because the Post Office had to take so many ex-service men, that
 was part of the - the set-up - so that a man when he came out job the Army or the Navy wouldn't be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 thrown on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 the unemployment scrap heap - he'd have a job and therefore the Post Office had to see that they - there were certain - certain number of posts fo
r these chappies. And of course when war broke out many of them were reservists and they were called up so I then passed onto a full time }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 postman\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  duty. Now, in the course of the duty with going round, I did the same what you would call walk each day and 
consequently you got to know all the people and there - you'd often have a chat with them, if they wanted anything or you could help them in any way you would do so. I remember on one occasion going to a house and this lady came to the door, she was very 
u
pset, she said my husbands in the police, when you go down to the telephone box will you ring him up and ask him - to come home at once, my little boy is ill. Little boy I think had the scarlet fever of course they didn't know at the time to what extent. 
But any little thing like that you did, oh yes, and - people were very friendly and - as many cases you could help them, they were always pleased to get a letter - and - I - I really enjoyed that side of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What were the hours for a full time postman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Well the hours - unfortunately - I suppose call it unfortunately I lived in Stoneycroft at the time and I was appointed - my brother was in the office and of course he was at the Eastern District Office so it was a rule that two brothers were not su
pposed to work at the same office so I - I had to go to the Northern District Office which was then about - oh, a good three miles from home. I don't know how it was but at the particular time, although I did have a cycle, at that particular time I - my o
w
n, yes, my own, 'cos cycles then, you could buy a nice bike for about thirty - thirty or thirty'five shillings they were very - you could buy secondhand very reasonable, I had a cycle but it may be - it may have been that - with going out you see you'd fi
n
ish on a delivery sometimes therefore your cycle would be - be - if - if you'd used a cycle it would be at the office and we - you would have to go back almost the same distance pick your bike up as you would to go home, so I think that was the reason but
 
I know very, very often I had to get up at four in the morning to get - to have my breakfast and then set off for the Northern District - Office. But I liked the work. The staff were very nice - they were a very nice crowd of chaps. We got on very well to
gether, I enjoyed the work, so I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 How many hours would you have worked as a full time postman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Eight hours a day but it was - unfortunately in those days it was split duty - practically all duties were split. Well you did - you started out - yo
u walked from home to the office, you stayed - did about an hour, hour and a half preparation, sorting, getting the walk out then you'd - everyone had - supposed to leave the office at seven o'clock. You'd walk about twenty minutes to the start of your de
l
ivery point and then from twenty past seven to half past eight you'd be delivering letters. Half past eight you'd finish in my particular case it was part of the way home so from where I finished to home would be about - oh a good hours walk, or well, thr
e
e quarter of an hours walk, and then the same coming - coming I'd take perhaps the keys - letterbox keys with me home and then on the way into the office I'd collect the boxes; perhaps six boxes on the way in - to the office and of course we then turn the
 
bag out face them up, put them through the stamping machine, sorted them into counties of England, tied them up, they were put in bags and sent to head office for - resorting again into the towns and villages. The work was - it was interesting. The only s
a
d part about it was, with being on a particular area you got to know the people, well at the time the boys would be called up - they were starting Kitchener's Army then, there was no conscription, it was just boys volunteering for the forces. Well in Live
rpool there were - about six battalions of infantry but they - they were all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2260340\charrsid4933843 Territorials}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
. There was the fifth, the sixth, the seventh, the eights which was the eighth Irish they call them, nearly all Irish boys, the ninth and the tenth Scottish. That's six
 battalions of infantry. There were about four brigades of - field artillery including halter batter - heavy battery, engineers, signalers - practically a whole division which afterwards formed the - thirtieth division for the forces - in the 14 - 18 war,
 
they were - they went out into the 14 - now a lot of these boys trained and then they went down to the South of England, mostly round Kent, near the coast - to be near - for going overseas. Now, a lot of the boys that I knew through delivery - through goi
n
g round the neighbourhood you got to know them with passing them each day and speaking - to them and that - they were - as they went out to France so you would be delivering letters from them from overseas and then unfortunately the time came when you wer
e delivering letters saying that the boys had been killed in action and - it - it upset me - yes, it upset me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 
As I said there were three chums at school - there was myself, John Fitzpatrick and William Graham, and we chummed together and we used to go - we
 didn't do any of the things you shouldn't do - we didn't smoke and we did a lot of walking and we made up that if we joined the Army we'd three would go into the same - unit to be together. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
Unfortunately - Fitzpatrick he had - he worked in town, at an off
ice in town and each day, he was quite a biggish boy, he wasn't eighteen, round seventeen mark, quite a big boy, and each day people would - would collar him and ask - wouldn't he like to join the Army and then although you weren't forced to do it - be as
k
ed so many times that in the end - if you have that - if you had that inclinations you did it so John joined the - Eighth Irish I Eighth Liverpools. Now Willie Graham unfortunately had a ghost appendicitis - he had appendix trouble - I remember him going 
i
nto the Southern Hospital - I remember I used to go down to see him when he was there and I don't know - he didn't seem to strong, but in the operation - he had a back wound - I don't know why, whether they had to approach him from the back to do this ope
ration, but they found out, when they eventually called him up for the forces he couldn't carry a pack. Well, in between these things -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 What were visiting hours at the hospital and what was it like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Well they were - they were much as the same as they are today, yes, about couple - hour or two a day, oh yes, they were quite liberal -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Was he quite happy in hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 Oh yes, treated us very nice. Oh yes, oh yes, hospitals were very - very nice. What was - what - I don't think - some reason
 - mind you, latter years we had a hospital scheme where we used to pay so much of you - into hospital, but I think in those days if I remember rightly there was no charge. I don't remember them - that arising at all 'course I wouldn't actually come in co
n
tact with the hospital accept for visiting him but - the treatment was very good, everything was very good, there was no complaint about the hospital it was the Southern Hospital and it's still the Southern Hospital in Carl-Street, yes, oh yes, yes. Now, 
h
e, yes, he - he - eventually was called up for the - I think it was the Alfreton Bucks Light Infantry but in the meantime with being at the office I don't know whether it was - I think it was I'd worked very hard at the Christmastime and I had a breakdown
 
in health - not a - somebody said it was like a faint - and I wasn't - exhausted - and I wasn't too well. Now, the doctor who I - in the course of this when I didn't feel well we had a Post Office doctor who you had to see, he was the official doctor, you
 
had to see him you see. I went along to see him and I wasn't well in his surgery so he said oh you'd better go home and I'll come and see you. So when he came - and I remember I had a little rash on the side of my legs, that was the only thing. Now, he ch
e
cked me all over and examined me and he was a bit puzzled so when he looked at my legs he said I think you've got scarlet fever. So I said, oh, I don't think so, doctor. Well, he said, in any case I'm going to send you into hospital. If you were a scarlet
 
fever case in those days you had to go into hospital. Isolation you see. He said, I'm going to send you into hospital. I said, well I'm not going to go, see. So, he said well think about it. He sent the ambulance along and I wouldn't go you see, I - I did
n
't like the idea of going into hospital - I don't know why but at the back of my mind - the case of it being an isolation hospital - you'd be away from everyone for five - five weeks - it was five weeks you see. So when he found this out he came along the
 
next day and he said if you don't go when I send the ambulance the next time your brother and sister will not be allowed to work because they were very strict in those days. If you were - a case like that - a contact case - anyone in the house - it was mo
re or less isolated. So in the end I had to go into hospital. Well, I went into Mill Lane Hospital in - in Mill Lane, Old Swan. They said when I arrived I was as funny a case as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 Scarlet}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  they'd ever seen. The sister said to me oh, but you'll have to stay in 
bed Tommy for three weeks - that's no matter whether you're ill or not. I remember having I first of all as soon as you got in you had to have a very hot bath and I remember feeling faint in the bath and helping me into bed but - I think I must have devel
o
ped it - whether I caught it there or not I or whether I did have it but I - I think I did have it but I didn't have it very severe - mild case. So at the end of three weeks I was up and I used to help in the wards and - yes. And I always remember, little
 things stand out in your mind, there was a gentleman came in every day, of course you were glad to see anyone to have a chat, and this man was a - I think he was a Methodist - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 
Congregational}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  Minister - Mr Lord - and he would come in and spend an hour eve
ry day at the bedside chatting and that and I got to like him very, very much. He was - he was a real kindly gentleman. Of course our own clergy came in from church - they came in every other day pretty well so I wasn't really lonely. Now the sister there
 was an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 exceedingly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 nice person - ah, very nice indeed, unfortunately she had - she was friendly with the doctor who was the Cap - he was also an Army Captain, he did - he was, I suppose he was loaned to the hospital. Perhaps I shouldn't mention his name. S
till I think - I think they were very friendly but - eventually he went off and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8812530 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 someone else and I think she was very upset about it - she was a Sheffield girl - but whilst I was in the ward and I got on probably so well that she coaxed me to stay 
another week. Well, I was the oldest one in the ward. I remember - well I'd be nineteen - what was - 1915 - 1914 would it be - seventeen - about sixteen or seventeen, about seventeen, perhaps seventeen I would be then. But - I remember the - the - this pr
i
est coming in and he said Tommy, what - ever you do don't stay in the hospital long because you may pick something else up. They also did Dip cases - they had a diphtheria ward just above it and I remember one evening they bought a little child in with di
p
 and - Hudson who was the medical officer said, oh, can't do anything, he's too far gone, you see, and off he went. Well that - later on a very old doctor came in who was a kind of assistant - he used to come in every evening - so he said to the nurses, h
ow long will it take you to get a tr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
chy table ready? So she said, oh, quarter of an hour or so. They got the table ready and they did a trachy on this child - tracheotomy operation and it saved his life, the little kid, pulled round, got over it, yes, and 
of course this - this disgust us but the nurses weren't supposed to discuss anything with the patients but of course being older than the - they'd come and chat at - night - and I think one occasion - it was a Welsh nurse. - They were all very nice to me.
 
The Matron came - Sister and Matron came round - well, once or twice caught her talking. I think she - got a bit of choking off for it. But there was a little nurse there - oh there was a - a - a staff nurse called Laffy from Belfast, an Irish nurse, goin
g
 back so long I remember them very well, and there was a nurse Graves and I had a little bit of a crush on nurse Graves. And they used to come up the road singing - Boys in - the war had started then so it must have been about 1915, early part of '15 I th
ink it was, so what I'd be - '15 - I must have been nineteen then - no that's in '15 - no it must have been 1914 - '14 - '-5 - the Christmastime. So she come up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 the ward}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  singing the, you know, there's boy in khaki, boys in blue, here's the best and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 j}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
olly good luck to you. And they were really - real sports. Well, they'd make the bed and they're supposed to be brushing the cru}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
bs and they're knocking you with the brush and - playing all kin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6775719\charrsid4933843 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
s - they were really - real good sports and I really enjoyed being th
ere. Oh yes. They were very nice. In fact, I often used to go for months afterwards to call in - once a week down to see them and have a chat with them, oh yes, they were very nice indeed.
