uthampton we landed at Le Havre and we moved up to place called Ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14490136\charrsid4933843 rf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
leur which is a big camp about a mile or so - couple - two or three miles out of the town. We stayed a night there and then we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 entrained}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  up again up to the line. We came up to - we were going up on the Somme offensive. We pulled into - on - from there I think it was about two or three days getting orders and different things you see and it was }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 whilst}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  I was there that I came across the second battalion of the Liverpool Perils and met the - on
e of the few occasions I met anyone from home - I met a few of my old schoolboy friends there you see - unfortunately one of them was killed afterwards - the other boy pulled through. But that was the first occasion I'd seen a man - tied to the gun wheel 
-
 they had a punishment in France called first field punishment - if you did anything seriously wrong you were tied to a gun wheel for so many hours a day and this chappie was tied in the middle of the square his arms stretched out tied with rope to a gun 
w
heel so they - one of the - well, corporal - wagon - one of the wagons. And that went on for some year or two until the French people complained about it. They said it was - it was - imitation of our Lord on the cross and the French - French people object
e
d. Then one or two of the chaps died with - through it - oh yes, oh yes. But discipline was much harder then - much stricter. So we were on the Somme then for - from 19 - that was 1916 - about April '16 - April - May - we were there on - the first of July
 
started the Somme offensive - I remember that quite well. As this - the - Major spoke about the number of rounds we fired well, we had to - collect about five thousand rounds of ammunition and we moved them from the railhead at night time - we - we had th
e
 wagons and go to railhead get this ammunition, bring it up to where the battery were - four guns, and carry it across a ploughed field, put it in the magazine that they'd made and so for about a fortnight we were getting - going - instead of going to bed
 
at night we went to the railhead, took this ammunition and - everything had to be done at night so the enemy couldn't see it. And so we did that until we had five thousand rounds of ammunition stored. Very often we'd get back and might only have a couple 
of hours sleep and then be on again - looking after the horses, because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 horses}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 have to be watered and fed three times a day and then there was of course the cleaning - you had to clean their horses the harness and - there was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 routine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843  for it you see. Well,
 the Somme offensive started and we moved up from there to Becordle, the Nets, Highwood, Thrones wood, Death Valley, I remember the first day of the Somme - of the Somme offensive and - oh we lost thousands and thousands of men - I managed to get away - I
 
don't know how I managed it but I managed to get a - away just have a look at the - what had - the line where our troops had been. The - the Germans were in dug trenches - they'd been there for months and months and they had them just like houses - they h
a
d all lined with wood well deep in the ground. When our people started they bombarded for about a week before they went over but as soon as they went over the Germans just came out of these wooden places and met our chaps and must machine gunned them.. 'C
ourse that was the idea at that time you just went up in a bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 dy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
 to take a trench, well that's - actually afterwards they learned to go up in strictly log formations but - as they were well they just moved them down. I remember going up and seeing all these 
bodies - thousands - there wasn't must a few - there were thousands of bodies - there were just gas mask on digging big graves putting twenty - thirty - perhaps a hundred men and then just covering them up. I suppose afterwards the war graves commission c
ame and - but that was the - through the Somme offensive.
