\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9197408 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 When you came back - 19 when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7166200 TB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 
Well what happened was - the war ended and instead of going into Germany we pulled out, we came back to - a little village, Braisce Somme, near Amiens and we
 were there and in the meantime I had - taken over as - to look after the horses - I was - signaller then - I - I - I jumped from driving into signaling - I was in signals section. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 
There were thirty-two others when I joined them - there were only six of us
 came through - all the rest were killed and wounded. I was with this officer and - and I used to keep an eye on his chargers - of course if I wanted a horse to - if he was going anywhere and I went with him I could always pick one of the light horses to 
g
o with him. We came - we had Christmas there and I was due for a leave - so on the - early in January 1919 I came home to England for - on leave. When we arrived in England we were taken down to Folkestone to a big - camp they had there. Actually they wer
e all the houses on the front were boarded - had very high boards put all round them and they'd used them during the war as centres for the troops going overseas so of course when the chaps came on leave they used them as leave centres. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572670\charrsid4933843 Well whilst we were 
there, there was a bit of a riot, a lot of the chaps wanted - clamming for demobilisation - people getting restive you see being in the war - some had been in since 1914, those that were lucky to pull through. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6837232\charrsid4933843 So they got us out of there as quickly as they
 could - I came home on leave and day or so after I - home - I was called at the office and they said, oh - would you like to come back right away? So I said I don't mind - I'd have enough of the Army so they gave me papers and I sent them up to my unit a
n
d I had instructions then to go to Heaton Park Manchester. I was demobilised there. I came back to the Post Office - and resumed the rank I had before - postman. I was one of the first back as a matter of fact. The first opportunity some - about six month
s
